# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: c-span
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] The **112th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, from January 3, 2011, until January 3, 2013.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] It convened in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2011, and ended on January 3, 2013, 17 days before the end of the presidential term to which Barack Obama was elected in 2008.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Senators elected to regular terms in 2006 completed those terms in this Congress.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] This Congress included the last House of Representatives elected from congressional districts that were apportioned based on the 2000 census.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] In the 2010 midterm elections, the Republican Party won the majority in the House of Representatives.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] While the Democrats kept their Senate majority, it was reduced from the previous Congress.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] This was the first Congress in which the House and Senate were controlled by different parties since the 107th Congress (2001–2003).
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] It was also the first Congress since the 36th Congress (1859–1861) in which the Republican Party held the House but not the Senate.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, the House of Representatives had the largest number of Republican members, 242, since the 80th Congress (1947–1949).
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] This was the only Congress between the 79th (1945–1947) and the 117th (2021–2023) that did not include a member of the Kennedy family.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] As of 2022, this is the most recent Congress in which Democrats held a Senate seat in Nebraska or a House seat in Arkansas, the last in which Republicans held both Senate seats in Maine, and the last in which Democrats did not hold all seats in Connecticut.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] A failure to pass a 2011 federal budget nearly led to a shutdown of non-essential government services on April 9, 2011, with the furlough of 800,000 government employees appearing imminent.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] President Obama met Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid and House Speaker John Boehner in the days preceding the deadline but was unable to come to an agreement to pass a budget.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] A one-week budget was proposed to avoid a government shutdown and allow more time for negotiations; however, proposals from both parties could not be accommodated.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Obama said he would veto a proposed Republican budget over Republican social spending cuts.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] This was also backed by Senate Democrats who objected to such cuts as that of Planned Parenthood.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] However, an agreement was reached between the two parties for a one-week budget to allow for more time to negotiate after Republicans dropped their stance on the Planned Parenthood issue.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] The two parties ultimately agreed on a 2011 federal budget the following week.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] There were many reactions to the possible shutdown with some saying the economy could be hurt during a fragile recovery and others saying the lack of an unnecessary bureaucracy would not be noticed.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] There was also criticism that while senators and representatives would continue to get paid others such as the police and military personnel would either not be paid for their work or have their payments deferred.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] On August 2, 2011, the United States public debt was projected to reach its statutory maximum.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Without an increase in that limit the U.S.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Treasury would be unable to borrow money to pay its bills.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Although previous statutory increases have been routine, conservative members of the House refused to allow an increase without drastically reducing government spending.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] Over several weeks and months, negotiators from both parties, both houses, and the White House worked to forge a compromise.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] The compromise bill, the Budget Control Act of 2011, was enacted on August 2.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] For the first time in the history of Congress, over half its members were millionaires as of 2012; Democrats had a median net worth of $1.04 million, while the Republicans median was "almost exactly" $1.00 million.
[src:c-span/112th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 2012; Class 2 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 2014; and Class 3 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 2016.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 3, 1992.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic ticket of Arkansas governor Bill Clinton and Tennessee junior senator Al Gore defeated incumbent Republican president George H.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and vice president Dan Quayle and the independent ticket of businessman Ross Perot and vice admiral James Stockdale.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush had alienated many conservatives in his party by breaking his 1988 campaign pledge not to raise taxes, but he fended off a primary challenge from paleoconservative commentator Pat Buchanan without losing a single contest.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's popularity following his success in the Gulf War dissuaded high-profile Democratic candidates such as Mario Cuomo from entering the 1992 Democratic primaries.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton, a leader of the centrist Democratic Leadership Council, established himself as the front-runner for the Democratic nomination by sweeping the Super Tuesday primaries.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He defeated former governor of California Jerry Brown, former Massachusetts senator Paul Tsongas, and other candidates to win the nomination, and chose Tennessee senator Al Gore as his running mate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The billionaire Perot launched an independent campaign, emphasizing his opposition to the North American Free Trade Agreement (which at time was being actively negotiated) and his plan to reduce the national debt.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The economy had recovered from a recession in the spring of 1991, followed by 19 consecutive months of growth, but perceptions of the economy's slow growth harmed Bush, for he had inherited a substantial economic boom from his predecessor Ronald Reagan.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's greatest strength, foreign policy, was regarded as much less important following the dissolution of the Soviet Union and the end of the Cold War, as well as the relatively peaceful climate in the Middle East after the Gulf War.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perot led in several polls taken in June 1992, but severely damaged his candidacy by temporarily dropping out of the race in July.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Bush campaign criticized Clinton's character and emphasized Bush's foreign policy successes, while Clinton focused on the economy.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton flipped a total of 22 states that had voted Republican in the election of 1988.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perot won 18.9% of the popular vote, the highest share of the vote won by a candidate outside of the two major parties since 1912.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the most recent presidential election in which a third-party candidate received more votes than at least one major party candidate in any state (Maine and Utah).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Due to the three-way split, only two contests were won by an absolute majority (Arkansas and Washington D.C.).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following the successful performance by U.S. and coalition forces in the Persian Gulf War, President George H.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His re-election was considered very likely; several high-profile candidates, such as Mario Cuomo and Jesse Jackson, refused to seek the Democratic nomination.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Al Gore from Tennessee refused to seek the nomination due to the fact his son had been struck by a car and was undergoing surgery and physical therapy; however, Tom Harkin, Paul Tsongas, Jerry Brown, Larry Agran, Bob Kerrey, Douglas Wilder, and Bill Clinton chose to run as candidates.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator from Iowa, ran as a populist liberal with labor union support.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator from Massachusetts, highlighted his political independence and fiscal conservatism.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Jerry Brown, the former California governor who had run for the Democratic nomination in 1976 and 1980, declared a significant reform agenda, including Congressional term limits, campaign finance reform, and the adoption of a flat income tax.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nebraska senator Bob Kerrey was an attractive candidate based on his business and military background, but made several gaffes on the campaign trail.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Arkansas governor Bill Clinton positioned himself as a centrist, or New Democrat.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was relatively unknown nationally before the primary season.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] That quickly changed when Gennifer Flowers alleged an extramarital affair.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton denied the story, appearing on *60 Minutes* with his wife, Hillary Clinton; later in 1998, he admitted the affair.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The primary began with Harkin winning his native Iowa as expected.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Tsongas won the New Hampshire primary on February 18, but Clinton's second-place finish, helped by his speech labeling himself "The Comeback Kid", energized his campaign.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Brown won the Maine caucus and Kerrey won South Dakota.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won his first primary in Georgia.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Tsongas won the Utah and Maryland primaries and a caucus in Washington.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Harkin won caucuses in Idaho and Minnesota while Brown won Colorado.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won the South Carolina and Wyoming primaries and Tsongas won Arizona.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton swept nearly all of the Super Tuesday primaries on March 10 making him the solid front runner.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won the Michigan and Illinois primaries.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Tsongas dropped out after finishing third in Michigan; however, Brown began to pick up steam, aided by using a phone number to receive funding from small donors.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Brown scored surprising wins in Connecticut, Vermont and Alaska.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the race moved to the primaries in New York and Wisconsin, Brown had taken the lead in polls in both states.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Then he made a serious gaffe by announcing to an audience of New York City's Jewish community that he would consider Reverend Jackson as a vice presidential candidate; Jackson had offended many Jewish people with remarks he had made during his own presidential campaigns.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won dramatically in New York (41%–26%) and closely in Wisconsin (37%–34%).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton then proceeded to win a long streak of primaries leading up to Brown's home state of California.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won this state 48% to 41% and secured the delegates needed to lock the nomination.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton chose Gore to be his running mate on July 9, 1992.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Choosing fellow Southerner Gore went against the popular strategy of balancing a Southern candidate with a Northern partner.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore served to balance the ticket in other ways, as he was perceived as strong on family values and environmental issues, while Clinton was not.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore's similarities to Clinton also allowed him to push some of his key campaign themes, such as centrism and generational change.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] President Bush had the public support and endorsement of former President Ronald Reagan and the Republican Party establishment.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan's best showing was in the New Hampshire primary on February 18, 1992—where Bush won by a 53–38% margin.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] President Bush won 73% of all primary votes, with 9,199,463 votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan won 2,899,488 votes; unpledged delegates won 287,383 votes, and David Duke, Grand Wizard of the Ku Klux Klan, won 119,115 votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Just over 100,000 votes were cast for all other candidates, half of which were write-in votes for H.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former Minnesota governor Harold Stassen, who had run for president nine times since 1944, also mounted his final campaign.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and Vice President Dan Quayle easily won renomination by the Republican Party.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, the success of the opposition forced the moderate Bush to move further to the right than in the previous election, and to incorporate many socially conservative planks in the party platform.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush allowed Buchanan to give a prime time address at the Republican National Convention in Houston, Texas, and his "Culture War" speech alienated liberal Republicans.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Vice President Dan Quayle was renominated by voice vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The public's concern about the federal budget deficit and fears of professional politicians led to the independent candidacy of billionaire Texan Ross Perot increasing in popularity in the polls—at one point Perot was leading the major party candidates.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perot crusaded against the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), and internal and external national debt, tapping into voters' potential fear of the deficit.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His volunteers succeeded in collecting enough signatures to get his name on the ballot in all 50 states.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In June, Perot led the national public opinion polls with support from 39% of the voters (versus 31% for Bush and 25% for Clinton).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perot severely damaged his credibility by dropping out of the presidential contest in July and remaining out of the race for several weeks before re-entering.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He compounded this damage by eventually claiming, without evidence, that his withdrawal was due to Republican operatives attempting to disrupt his daughter's wedding.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perot and retired Vice Admiral James Stockdale drew **19,743,821** votes (19% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 6th Libertarian Party National Convention was held in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There, the Libertarian Party nominated Andre Marrou, former Alaska State Representative and the Party's 1988 vice presidential candidate, for president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Marrou and Lord drew 291,627 votes (0.28% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Lenora Fulani, who was the 1988 presidential nominee of the New Alliance Party, received a second consecutive nomination from the Party in 1992.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unlike in 1988, Fulani failed to gain ballot access in every state, deciding to concentrate some of that campaign funding towards exposure of her candidacy and the Party to the national public.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Fulani also sought the endorsement of the Peace and Freedom Party of California, but despite winning a majority in that party's primary, she would lose the nomination to Ronald Daniels, the former Director the National Rainbow Coalition.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Rather than pursuing a ballot space of her own, Fulani would endorse Daniels's candidacy in California.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Fulani and her running mate Maria Elizabeth Muñoz received 73,622 votes (0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The newly formed Natural Law Party nominated scientist and researcher John Hagelin for president and Mike Tompkins for vice president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Natural Law Party had been founded in 1992 by Hagelin and 12 others who felt that governmental problems could be solved more effectively by following "Natural Laws".
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party platform included preventive health care, sustainable agriculture and renewable energy technologies.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During this and future campaigns, Hagelin favored abortion rights without public financing, campaign finance law reform, improved gun control, a flat tax, the eradication of PACs, a ban on soft money contributions, and school vouchers.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party's first presidential ticket appeared on the ballot in 28 states and drew 37,137 votes (<0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taxpayers Party ran its first presidential ticket in 1992, having only been formed the prior year.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially Howard Phillips had hoped to successfully entice a prominent conservative politician, such as the former senator Gordon J.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Humphrey from New Hampshire, or even Patrick Buchanan who at the time had only been mulling over running against President Bush (he would officially declare in December 1991).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] No one, however, announced any intention to seek the Taxpayers Party nomination; Buchanan himself in the end endorsed President Bush at the Republican National Convention in Houston.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Phillips had been unofficially nominated earlier in the year so as to allow the Party to be able to seek ballot access properly.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While initially a temporary post, it was made permanent at the party's national convention, which was held in New Orleans on September 4 and 5.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the convention, which was attended by delegates from thirty-two states and Washington, D.C., Phillips received 264 votes on the first ballot, while Albion Knight was approved as his running mate by acclamation.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Earlier that year, in the June 2 California primary, Phillips had received 15,456 votes in the American Independent Party primary.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 30, the American Independent Party voted to affiliate with the U.S.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taxpayers Party, an affiliation which continued until 2008.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Phillips and Knight drew 43,369 votes (<0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former United States Army Special Forces officer and Vietnam veteran Bo Gritz was the nominee of the Populist Party, facing virtually no opposition.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, Gritz openly proclaimed the United States to be a "Christian Nation", stating that the country's legal statutes "should reflect unashamed acceptance of Almighty God and His Laws".
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His run on the America First/Populist Party ticket was prompted by his association with another far-right political Christian talk radio host, Tom Valentine.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During his campaign, part of Gritz's standard stump speech was an idea to pay off the national debt by minting a coin at the Treasury and sending it to the Federal Reserve.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This predates the 2012 trillion-dollar coin concept.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During August 1992, Gritz attracted national attention as mediator during the government standoff with Randy Weaver at Ruby Ridge, Idaho.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He received 106,152 votes nationwide (0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In two states he had a respectable showing for a minor third-party candidate: Utah, where he received 3.8% of the vote and Idaho, where he received 2.1% of the vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In some counties, his support topped 10%, and in Franklin County, Idaho, was only a few votes away from pushing Bill Clinton into fourth place in the county.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While officially running for the Democratic presidential nomination, Lyndon LaRouche also decided to run as an Independent in the general election, standing as the **National Economic Recovery** candidate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] LaRouche was in jail at the time, having been convicted of conspiracy to commit mail fraud in December 1988; it was only the second time in history that the presidency was sought from a prison cell (after Socialist Party candidate Eugene V.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Debs, while imprisoned for his opposition to U.S. involvement in World War I, ran in 1920).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His running-mate was James Bevel, a civil rights activist who had represented the LaRouche movement in its pursuit of the Franklin child prostitution ring allegations.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition to the displayed states, LaRouche had nearly made the ballot in the states of New York and Mississippi.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ohio also had a sore-loser law, but it was ruled in Brown vs.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Taft that it did not apply to presidential candidates.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] James Warren, who was the 1988 presidential nominee of the Socialist Workers Party, received a second consecutive nomination from the Party on the first of November 1991.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Warren had two running mates that varied from state to state; Estelle DeBates and Willie Mae Reid, the latter also a resident of Illinois.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Warren received 22,882 votes (<0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ronald Daniels was the former executive director for the Center for Constitutional Rights, the former director of the National Rainbow Coalition, and the worked on both of Jesse Jackson's campaigns for the Democratic presidential nomination.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Asiba Tupahache, a Native American activist from New York was his running-mate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Daniels and Tupachache drew 27,396 votes (<0.1% of the popular vote).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 1992 campaign also marked the entry of Ralph Nader into presidential politics as a candidate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite the advice of several liberal and environmental groups, Nader did not formally run.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Rather, he tried to make an impact in the New Hampshire primaries, urging members of both parties to write-in his name.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As a result, several thousand Democrats and Republicans wrote-in Nader's name.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite supporting mostly liberal legislation during his career as a consumer advocate, Nader received more votes from Republicans than Democrats.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Worker's League nominated Helen Halyard for president; she was the party's nominee for vice president in 1984 and 1988.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Fred Mazelis was nominated for vice president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John Yiamouyiannis, a major opponent of water fluoridation, ran as an Independent under the label **"Take Back America"**.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Yiamouyiannis and McCone drew 2,199 votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Quinn Brisben for president and Barbara Garson for vice president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Grassroots Party nominated Jack Herer, a noted cannabis activist for president and Derrick Grimmer for vice president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Prohibition Party nominated Earl Dodge, the party's chairman for president and George Ormsby for vice president.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Drew Bradford was an Independent candidate for the Presidency; he did not have a running-mate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Delbert Ehlers was an Independent candidate for the Presidency.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Bill Clinton secured the Democratic Party's nomination in the spring of 1992, polls showed Ross Perot leading the race, followed by President Bush and Clinton in third place after a grueling nomination process.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Two-way trial heats between Bush and Clinton in early 1992 showed Bush in the lead.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the economy continued to sour and the President's approval rating continued to slide, the Democrats began to rally around their nominee.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 9, 1992, Clinton chose Tennessee senator and former 1988 presidential candidate Al Gore to be his running mate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As Governor Clinton's nomination acceptance speech approached, Ross Perot dropped out of the race, convinced that staying in the race with a "revitalized Democratic Party" would cause the race to be decided by the United States House of Representatives.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton gave his acceptance speech on July 16, 1992, promising to bring a "new covenant" to America, and to work to heal the gap that had developed between the rich and the poor during the Reagan/Bush years.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Clinton campaign received the biggest convention "bounce" in history which brought him from 25% in the spring, behind Bush and Perot, to 55% versus Bush's 31%.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the convention, Clinton and Gore began a bus tour around the United States, while the Bush/Quayle campaign began to criticize Clinton's character, highlighting accusations of infidelity and draft dodging.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Bush campaign emphasized its foreign policy successes such as Desert Storm, and the end of the Cold War.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush also contrasted his military service to Clinton's lack thereof, and criticized Clinton's lack of foreign policy expertise.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, as the economy was the main issue, Bush's campaign floundered across the nation, even in strongly Republican areas, and Clinton maintained leads with over 50% of the vote nationwide consistently, while Bush typically saw numbers in the upper 30s.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As Bush's economic edge had evaporated, his campaign looked to energize its socially conservative base at the 1992 Republican National Convention in Houston, Texas.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the convention, Bush's primary campaign opponent Pat Buchanan gave his famous "culture war" speech, criticizing Clinton's and Gore's social progressiveness, and voicing skepticism on his "New Democrat" brand.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After President Bush accepted his renomination, his campaign saw a small bounce in the polls, but this was short-lived, as Clinton maintained his lead.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaign continued with a lopsided lead for Clinton through September, until Ross Perot decided to re-enter the race.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The race narrowed, as Perot's numbers significantly improved as Clinton's numbers declined, while Bush's numbers remained more or less the same from earlier in the race as Perot and Bush began to hammer at Clinton on character issues once again.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton was often accused of being a philanderer by political opponents.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Allegations were also made that Bill Clinton had engaged in a long-term extramarital affair with Gennifer Flowers.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton denied ever having an affair with Flowers, but later admitted, under threat of perjury, that he had a brief sexual encounter with her in 1977.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton was declared the winner by CBS, NBC, and CNN at 10:48 P.M.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He received 370 electoral votes from 32 states and D.C. and 43% of the popular vote while Bush received 168 electoral votes from 18 states and 37.4% of the popular vote and Perot received 18.9% of the popular vote and no electoral votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The remaining candidates took 0.6% of the popular vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While winning the popular vote, Clinton did not win a majority of the popular vote; he was the first presidential candidate since Richard Nixon in 1968 to win the popular vote with a plurality, and the first Democrat since John F.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Only Washington, D.C., and Clinton's home state of Arkansas gave the majority of their votes to a single candidate in the entire country; the rest were won by pluralities of the vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton was the first Democrat since 1964 to win a majority of states.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even though Clinton received roughly 3,100,815 more votes than Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis had four years earlier, the Democrats recorded a 2.7 percentage point *decrease* in their share of the popular vote compared to 1988 due to the higher turnout.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His 43% share of the popular vote was the second-lowest for any winning candidate in the 20th century after Woodrow Wilson in 1912 (41.8%).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] President Bush's 37.4% was the lowest percentage total for a sitting president seeking re-election since William Howard Taft, also in 1912 (23.2%).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 1992 was, as the 1912 election was, a three-way race (that time between Taft, Wilson, and Theodore Roosevelt).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was also the lowest percentage for a major-party candidate since Alf Landon received 36.5% of the vote in 1936.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush had a lower percentage of the popular vote than even Herbert Hoover, who was defeated in 1932 (39.7%).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, none of these races included a major third-party candidate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Independent candidate Ross Perot received 19,743,821 with 18.9% of the popular vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Speaking about the North American Free Trade Agreement, Perot described its effect on American jobs as causing a "giant sucking sound".
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For a period of time, Perot was leading in the polls, but he lost much of his support when he temporarily withdrew from the election, only to declare himself a candidate again soon after.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the most recent time that a non-major party candidate and a non-party affiliated candidate won at least one county.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Perot's 18.9% of the popular vote made him the most successful non-major party presidential candidate in terms of popular vote since Theodore Roosevelt in the 1912 election.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His share of the popular vote was also the highest ever for a candidate who did not win any electoral votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Perot also came in 2nd in Maine's 2nd Congressional District, where he had his best overall showing, winning 33.2% of the vote there and missing the district's 1 elector by only 4.6% of the vote.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was the most recent in which Montana voted for the Democratic candidate, both the last time Florida backed the losing candidate and last time Georgia voted for the Democratic candidate until 2020, and the last time that Colorado voted Democratic until 2008.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton became the second Democrat to win every electoral vote in the Northeast, the first being Lyndon B.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] John Kerry and Barack Obama have been the only Democrats to repeat this since.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Also, this was the first time since 1964 that the following nine states had voted Democratic: California, Colorado, Illinois, Montana, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New Mexico, and Vermont.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt's 1,876 total electoral votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush and Clinton achieved an exact tie in Ware County, Georgia, the most recent time in American history a county was tied between the two major-party presidential candidates.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Perot also achieved an exact tie with Bush in Morris County, Kansas.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Several factors made the results possible.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] First, the campaign came on the heels of an economic slowdown.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Exit polling showed that 75% thought the economy was in fairly or very bad shape while 63% thought their personal finances were better or the same as four years ago.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The decision by Bush to accept a tax increase adversely affected his re-election bid.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Pressured by rising budget deficits, Bush agreed to a budget compromise with Congress which raised taxes and reduced the federal budget deficit.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton was able to condemn the tax increase effectively on both its own merits and as a reflection of Bush's dishonesty.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Effective Democratic TV ads were aired showing a clip of Bush's 1988 acceptance speech in which he promised "Read my lips ...
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] No new taxes." Most importantly, Bush's coalition was in disarray, for both the aforementioned reasons and for unrelated reasons.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The end of the Cold War allowed old rivalries among conservatives to re-emerge and meant that other voters focused more on domestic policy, to the detriment of Bush, a social and fiscal moderate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The consequence of such a perception depressed conservative turnout.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was compared to the 1945 United Kingdom general election, in which Winston Churchill, while a respected conservative wartime leader (like Bush) was not regarded as a good peacetime leader, and thus was voted out once the conflict was over.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Unlike Bush, Clinton was able to unite his fractious and ideologically diverse party behind his candidacy, even when its different wings conflicted.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] To garner the support of moderates and conservative Democrats, he attacked Sister Souljah, an obscure rap musician whose lyrics Clinton condemned.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, Clinton made clear his support of the death penalty and would later champion making school uniforms in public schools a requirement.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton could also point to his centrist record as governor of Arkansas.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] More liberal Democrats were impressed by Clinton's record on abortion and affirmative action.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His strong connections to African Americans also played a key role.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In addition, he organized significant numbers of young voters and became a symbol of the rise of the baby boomer generation to political power.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Supporters remained energized and confident, even in times of scandal or missteps.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The effect of Ross Perot's candidacy has been a contentious point of debate for many years.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the ensuing months after the election, various Republicans asserted that Perot had acted as a spoiler, enough to the detriment of Bush to lose him the election.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The voting numbers reveal that to win the electoral vote Bush would have had to win 10 of the 11 states Clinton won by less than five percentage points.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] For Bush to earn a majority of the popular vote, he would have needed 12.2% of Perot's 18.9% of the vote, 65% of Perot's support base.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] State exit polls suggested that Perot did not alter the electoral college count, except potentially in one state (Ohio), which nonetheless showed a result in the margin of error.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, Perot was most popular in states that strongly favored either Clinton or Bush, limiting his real electoral impact for either candidate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Perot gained relatively little support in the Southern states and happened to have the best showing in states with few electoral votes.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Perot appealed to disaffected voters all across the political spectrum who had grown weary of the two-party system.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] NAFTA played a role in Perot's support, and Perot voters were relatively moderate on hot-button social issues.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A 1999 study in the *American Journal of Political Science* estimated that Perot's candidacy hurt the Clinton campaign, reducing "Clinton's margin of victory over Bush by seven percentage point." In 2016, *FiveThirtyEight* noted that it was "unlikely" that Perot was a spoiler.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton, Bush, and Perot did not focus on abortion during the campaign.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Exit polls, however, showed that attitudes toward abortion "significantly influenced" the vote, as pro-choice Republicans defected from Bush.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The South was the only region where Bush received a majority of the electoral votes and two-thirds of his total electoral votes came from the South.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to Seymour Martin Lipset, this election had several unique characteristics.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters felt that economic conditions were worse than they actually were, which harmed Bush.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A rare event was a strong third-party candidate.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Liberals launched a backlash against 12 years of a conservative White House.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The chief factor was Clinton's uniting his party, and winning over a number of heterogeneous groups.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton's election ended an era in which the Republican Party had controlled the White House for 12 consecutive years, and for 20 of the previous 24 years.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election also brought the Democrats full control of the legislative and executive branches of the federal government, including both houses of U.S.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Congress and the presidency, for the first time since the administration of the last Democratic president, Jimmy Carter.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This would not last for very long, however, as the Republicans won control of both the House and Senate in 1994.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reelected in 1996, Clinton would become the first Democratic president since Franklin D.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt to serve two full terms in the White House and the first to leave office at the end of his second full term since Woodrow Wilson.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 1992 was arguably a political realignment election.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It made the Democratic Party dominant in presidential elections in the Northeast, the Great Lakes region, and the West Coast, where many states had previously either been swing states or Republican-leaning.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Vermont, carried by Clinton, had been heavily Republican for generations prior to the election, voting for a Democrat only once (in 1964).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The state has been won by the Democratic nominee in every presidential election since.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bill Clinton narrowly defeated Bush in New Jersey (by two points), which had voted for the Republican nominee all but twice since 1948.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton would later win the state in 1996 by eighteen points; like Vermont, Republicans have not won the state since.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] California, which had been a Republican stronghold since 1952, was now trending Democratic.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Clinton, a native Southerner, was able to carry several states in the South that the GOP had won for much of the past two decades, but ultimately won only four of eleven former Confederate states.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This reflected the final shift of the South to the Republican Party.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In subsequent presidential elections from 1996 to 2020, 28 out of the 50 states were carried by the same party as in 1992 (15 for the Democrats and 13 for the Republicans).
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] †Maine and Nebraska each allowed their electoral votes to be split between candidates using the Congressional District Method for electoral vote assignment.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In both states, two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote was awarded to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] District results for Maine and Nebraska do not include results for Marrou or other candidates and so totals differ from those for the states' at-large.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Because Perot finished in 2nd place in some districts, the margins of the districts do not match the margin at-large.
[src:c-span/1992-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nebraska split its electoral votes this way for the first time.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The **Northeast blackout of 2003** was a widespread power outage throughout parts of the Northeastern and Midwestern United States, and most parts of the Canadian province of Ontario on Thursday, August 14, 2003, beginning just after 4:10 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Most places restored power by midnight (within 7 hours), some as early as 6 p.m. on August 14 (within 2 hours), while the New York City Subway resumed limited services around 8 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Full power was restored to New York City and parts of Toronto on August 16.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] At the time, it was the world's second most widespread blackout in history, after the 1999 Southern Brazil blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The outage, which was much more widespread than the Northeast blackout of 1965, affected an estimated 55 million people, including 10 million people in southern and central Ontario and 45 million people in eight U.S. states.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The blackout was due to a software bug in the alarm system at the control room of FirstEnergy, which rendered operators unaware of the need to redistribute load after overloaded transmission lines dropped in voltage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] What should have been a manageable local blackout cascaded into the collapse of much of the Northeast regional electricity distribution system.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] According to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO)—the ISO, responsible for managing the New York state power grid—a 3,500 megawatt power surge (towards Ontario) affected the transmission grid at 4:10:39 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] For the next 30 minutes, until 4:40 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] EDT, outages were reported in parts of Michigan (Detroit), Ohio (Cleveland, Akron, Toledo), Ontario (Toronto, Hamilton, London, Windsor), New Jersey (Newark), and New York (New York City, Suffolk, Nassau, Westchester, Orange and Rockland counties, Rochester, Syracuse, Binghamton, Albany).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] This was followed by outages in other areas initially unaffected, including all of New York City, portions of southern New York state, New Jersey, Vermont, Connecticut, as well as most of the province of Ontario.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Eventually, a large, somewhat triangular area bounded by Lansing, Michigan, Sault Ste.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Marie, Ontario, the shore of James Bay, Ottawa, New York, and Toledo was left without power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] According to the official analysis of the blackout prepared by the US and Canadian governments, more than 508 generating units at 265 power plants shut down during the outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In the minutes before the event, the NYISO-managed power system was carrying 28,700 MW of load.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] At the height of the outage, the load had dropped to 5,716 MW, a loss of 80%.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Essential services remained in operation in some of these areas.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In others, backup generation systems failed.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Telephone networks generally remained operational, but the increased demand triggered by the blackout left some circuits overloaded.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Water systems in several cities lost pressure, forcing boil-water advisories to be put into effect.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Cellular service was interrupted as mobile networks were overloaded with the increase in volume of calls.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Multiple cell sites were out of commission due to power outages.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Television and radio stations remained on the air, with the help of backup generators, although some stations were knocked off the air for periods ranging from several hours to the length of the entire blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] High heat played a role in the initial event that triggered the wider power outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Much of the affected region reached temperatures higher than 31 °C (88 °F) that day, increasing energy demand as people across the region turned on fans and air conditioning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] This caused the power lines to sag as higher currents heated the lines.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Most of the Amtrak Northeast Corridor service was interrupted, as it relied on electricity for its signaling and crossing systems; electrified commuter railways also shut down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Via Rail in Canada was able to continue most of its service.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] All airports in the affected area closed immediately, there were no departures, and incoming flights had to be diverted to airports with power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The reliability of the electrical grid was called into question and required substantial investment to repair its shortcomings.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In areas where power remained off after nightfall, the Milky Way and orbiting artificial satellites became visible to the naked eye in metropolitan areas where they cannot ordinarily be seen due to light pollution.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Most places restored power by midnight, as early as 6 p.m. on August 14, and the New York City Subway had resumed limited services around 8 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] By the next morning (August 15), some areas of Manhattan regained power around 5:00 a.m.; Staten Island regained power around 3:00 a.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Half of the affected portions of Ontario regained power by the morning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] By early evening of August 15, two airports, Cleveland Hopkins International Airport and Toronto Pearson International Airport, were back in service.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] By August 16, power was fully restored in New York and parts of Toronto.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] 500,000 Detroit Edison customers were still without power at 10:00pm August 15; all were restored by 6:30am August 16.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Philadelphia and the surrounding mid-Atlantic areas were also completely unaffected because PJM disconnected them.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The Saint Clair power plant in East China Township, Michigan, remained online for about 36 hours, and residents were informed that the plant would have to shut down in order to facilitate the reboot of the whole system.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Orrville, Ohio, was able to restore power within an hour disconnecting the local utility from the larger grid and restarting the coal-fired generator.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The load on any power network must be immediately matched by its supply and its ability to transmit that power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Any overload of a power line or generator can cause costly damage, so the affected device is disconnected from the network if an overload is detected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The electrical resistance of a power line causes it to produce more heat as the current it carries increases.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If this heat is not sufficiently dissipated, the metal conductor in the line will expand and lengthen, so that it sags between supporting structures.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If the line sags too low, a flash over to nearby objects (such as trees) may occur, causing a transient increase in current.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Automatic protective relays detect the excessively high current and quickly disconnect the line, so the load previously carried by the line is transferred to other lines.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If the other lines do not have enough spare capacity to accommodate the extra current, their overload protection will react as well, causing a cascading failure.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] System operators are responsible for ensuring that power supply and loads remain balanced, and for keeping the system within safe operational limits such that no single fault can cause the system to fail.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In an emergency, they are expected to immediately shed load as required to bring the system into balance.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] To assist the operators there are computer systems, with backups, which issue alarms when there are faults in the transmission or generation system.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If the computer systems and their backups fail, the operators are required to monitor the grid manually, instead of relying on computer alerts.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If they cannot interpret the state of the power grid in such an event, they follow a contingency plan, contacting other plant and grid operators by telephone if necessary.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] If there is a failure, they are also required to notify adjacent areas which may be affected, so those can predict the possible effects on their own systems.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] A joint federal task force was formed by the governments of Canada and the U.S. to oversee the investigation and report directly to Ottawa and Washington.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The task force was led by then-Canadian Natural Resources Minister Herb Dhaliwal and U.S.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In addition to determining the initial cause of the cascading failure, the investigation of the incident also included an examination of the failure of safeguards designed to prevent a repetition of the Northeast blackout of 1965.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation, a joint Canada-U.S. council, is responsible for dealing with these issues.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] On November 19, 2003, Abraham said his department would not seek to punish FirstEnergy Corp for its role in the blackout because current U.S. law does not require electric reliability standards.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] This trip caused load to transfer to other transmission lines, which were not able to bear the load, tripping their breakers.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Once these multiple trips occurred, a number of generators suddenly lost parts of their loads, so they accelerated out of phase with the grid at different rates, and tripped out to prevent damage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The cascading effect that resulted ultimately forced the shutdown of at least 265 power plants.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] A software bug known as a race condition existed in General Electric Energy's Unix-based XA/21 energy management system.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Once triggered, the bug stalled FirstEnergy's control room alarm system for over an hour.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] System operators were unaware of the malfunction.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The failure deprived them of both audio and visual alerts for important changes in system state.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Unprocessed events queued up after the alarm system failure and the primary server failed within 30 minutes.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Then all applications (including the stalled alarm system) were automatically transferred to the backup server, which itself failed at 14:54.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The server failures slowed the screen refresh rate of the operators' computer consoles from 1–3 seconds to 59 seconds per screen.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The lack of alarms led operators to dismiss a call from American Electric Power about the tripping and reclosure of a 345 kV shared line in northeast Ohio.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] But by 15:42, after the control room itself lost power, control room operators informed technical support (who were already troubleshooting the problem) of the alarm system problem.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The cascading failure began in the FE-controlled Cleveland–Akron area; the area was significant because it was a "transmission-constrained load pocket with relatively limited generation." On August 14, a number of power generators in and around the area were offline.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] This reduced the available resources for voltage control and reactive power management in contingencies but did not affect normal operation.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Incidents contributing to the blackout began after noon on August 14.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] FE's reliability coordinator was the Midwest Independent System Operator (MISO).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] MISO maintained a regularly updated model of its area of responsibility with a state estimator (SE).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] At 12:15 p.m., the SE was mistakenly shutdown after producing anomalous results due to old data.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In the Cleveland-Akron area, Eastlake Power Plant unit 5 went offline at 1:31 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] In Southern Ohio, Dayton Power and Light's (DPL) Stuart-Atlanta transmission line tripped from tree contact at 2:02 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The outages did not affect normal operation.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] However, the loss of the Eastlake unit put the FE system at risk of overloads in certain contingency scenarios; FE did not notice the danger.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] At the time of the Eastlake unit outage, FE was asking for and receiving significant additional voltage support, but the situation was not unprecedented.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] FE's situational awareness was reduced by the development of faults in its General Electric Harris XA21 energy management system (EMS) from 2:14 p.m. to 2:54 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The alarm and logging software in the control room failed first, followed by some remote terminals and data links, then the primary and backup EMS servers.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Control room operators were unaware of the alarm failure for over an hour.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Operators began to suspect a failure after receiving a notification from American Electric Power (AEP) at 2:32 p.m. about a short AEP line outage that the FE EMS had failed to raise an alert for.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] FE IT was automatically notified of the remote terminal and server failures.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] IT performed a "warm reboot" of the primary server at 3:08 p.m. but did not realize that the alarm function remained broken.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The control room notified IT of the alarm problem at 3:42 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] A "cold reboot"—later discovered to be the vendor-recommended action—was rejected because the power system situation was precarious and operators were concerned about the greater loss of functionality during the reboot procedure.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The servers were offline again at 3:46 p.m. to 3:59 p.m. as they were rebooted in another attempt to re-enable the alarms.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] FE failed to notify MISO of its degraded situational awareness.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Cleveland-Akron area transmission lines began failing shortly after 3:00 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Three 345 kV transmission lines failed between 3:05 p.m. to 3:42 p.m. due to tree contact.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The first was the Harding-Chamberlin line.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Most of the load from that line was transferred to the Hanna-Juniper line, which then failed at 3:32 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] PJM and AEP began mitigation efforts to prevent the Star-South Canton line connecting FE and AEP from overloading; they had incomplete data on the status of FE's system and underestimated the severity of the situation.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The Star-South Canton line failed at 3:41 p.m. after its loading increased from 82% to 120% after the failure of the Hanna-Juniper line.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The failures in the MISO SE and FE EMS prevented either from recognizing and responding to the failures.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] FE observed the loss of voltage after 3:32 p.m, but it was not until 3:45 p.m. that it recognized an emergency was occurring.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] Next, the 138 kV lines failed between 3:39 p.m. to 4:08 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The loss of voltage shut down industrial equipment used by customers and blacked out Akron and its surroundings.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The MISO SE was reactivated at 2:40 p.m, but the results confused operators because the model did not match empirical data.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] The discrepancy was caused by the SE being unaware of the DPL line outage at 2:02 p.m; DPL's reliability coordinator was PJM, so DPL did not automatically report data to MISO.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] MISO operators had the SE modelling correctly again by 4:04 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p01] It was too late for MISO to address FE's critical status; the cascading failure started minutes later.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] With the power fluctuations on the grid, power plants automatically went into "safe mode" to prevent damage in the case of an overload.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] This put much of the nuclear power offline until those plants could be slowly taken out of "safe mode".
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the meantime, all available hydro-electric plants (as well as a number of coal- and oil-fired plants) were brought online, bringing some electrical power to the areas immediately surrounding the plants by the morning of August 15.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Homes and businesses both in the affected area and in nearby areas were requested to limit power usage until the grid was back to full power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some areas lost water pressure because pumps lacked power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] This loss of pressure caused potential contamination of the water supply.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Four million customers of the Detroit water system in eight counties were under a boil-water advisory until August 18, four days after the initial outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] One county, Macomb, ordered all 2,300 restaurants closed until they were decontaminated after the advisory was lifted.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Clair River claim to have been sickened after bathing in the river during the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The accidental release of 140 kg (310 lb) of vinyl chloride from a Sarnia, Ontario chemical plant was not revealed until five days later.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Cleveland also lost water pressure and instituted a boil water advisory.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Cleveland and New York had sewage spills into waterways, requiring beach closures.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Newark, New Jersey, and northern cities had major sewage spills into the Passaic and Hackensack rivers, which flow directly to the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Kingston, Ontario lost power to sewage pumps, causing raw waste to be dumped into the Cataraqui River at the base of the Rideau Canal.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Canada's Via Rail, which serves Toronto and Montreal, had a few service delays before returning to normal the next morning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Passenger screenings at affected airports ceased.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Regional airports were shut down for this reason.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In New York, flights were cancelled even after power had been restored to the airports because of difficulties accessing "electronic-ticket" information.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Air Canada flights remained grounded on the morning of August 15 due to reliable power not having been restored to its Mississauga control center.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] It expected to resume operations by midday.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] This problem affected all Air Canada service and canceled the most heavily traveled flights to Halifax and Vancouver.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] At Chicago's Midway International Airport, Southwest Airlines employees spent 48 hours dealing with the disorder caused by the blackout's sudden incidence.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Many gas stations were unable to pump fuel due to lack of electricity.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In North Bay, Ontario, for instance, a long line of transport trucks was held up, unable to go further west to Manitoba without refueling.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In some cities, traffic problems were compounded by motorists who simply drove until their cars ran out of gas on the highway.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Gas stations operating in pockets of Burlington, Ontario, that had power were reported to be charging prices up to $3.78 per US gallon (99.9 ¢/Litre) when the going rate prior to the blackout was lower than $2.65/gallon (70¢/L).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Customers still lined up for hours to pay prices many people considered price gouging.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Station operators claimed that they had a limited supply of gasoline and did not know when their tanks would be refilled, prompting the drastic price increases.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Many oil refineries on the East Coast of the United States shut down as a result of the blackout, and were slow to resume gasoline production.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] As a result, gasoline prices were expected to rise approximately 10 cents/gallon (3¢/L) in the United States.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Canada, gasoline rationing was also considered by the authorities.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Cellular communication devices were disrupted.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] This was mainly due to the loss of backup power at the cellular sites where generators ran out of fuel.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Where cell sites remained up, some cell phones still went out of service as their batteries ran out of charge without a power source to recharge from.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Wired telephone lines continued to work, although some systems were overwhelmed by the volume of traffic, and millions of home users had only cordless telephones depending on house current.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Most New York and multiple Ontario radio stations were momentarily knocked off the air before returning with backup power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Cable television systems were disabled, and in areas that had power restored (and had power to their television sets), cable subscribers could not receive information until power was restored to the cable provider.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Those who relied on the Internet were similarly disconnected from their news source for the duration of the blackout, with the exception of dial-up access from laptop computers, which were widely reported to work until the batteries ran out of charge.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Information was available by over-the-air TV and radio reception for those who were equipped to receive TV and/or audio in that way.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The blackout affected communications well outside the immediate area of power outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The New Jersey–based internet operations of Advance Publications were among those knocked out by the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] As a result, the internet editions of Advance newspapers as far removed from the blackout area as *The Birmingham News*, the New Orleans *Times-Picayune*, and *The Oregonian* were offline for days.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Amateur radio operators passed emergency communications during the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Large numbers of factories were closed in the affected area, and others outside the area were forced to close or slow work because of supply problems and the need to conserve energy while the grid was being stabilized.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] At one point a 7-hour wait developed for trucks crossing the Ambassador Bridge between Detroit and Windsor due to the lack of electronic border check systems.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Freeway congestion in affected areas affected the "just in time" (JIT) supply system.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some industries (including the auto industry) did not return to full production until August 22.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Almost the entirety of the State of New York lost power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] There were also some small pockets of power in the suburbs of Rochester, as a few smaller power companies operating in those areas were able to keep running.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The North Shore Towers complex was unaffected by the blackout due to their on-site self-generating power plant.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Power was also available at the Kodak Park facility and its surrounding neighborhood in the city.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Power was lost at the Oak Hill Country Club in nearby Pittsford, where the 2003 PGA Championship was being played, which caused minor interruptions to the tournament.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Also, that evening's Major League Baseball game between the New York Mets and the San Francisco Giants at Shea Stadium was postponed.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In New York, all prisons were blacked out and switched to generator power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The two Indian Point nuclear reactors on the Hudson River near Peekskill, the two reactors at Nine Mile Point nuclear plant, the single reactor at Ginna nuclear plant near Rochester, and the FitzPatrick reactor near Oswego all shut down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] With three other nuclear plants shut down in Ohio, Michigan, and New Jersey, a total of nine reactors were affected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The governor of New York, George Pataki, declared a state of emergency.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Verizon's emergency generators failed several times, leaving the emergency services number 9-1-1 out of service for several periods of about a quarter-hour each.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] New York City's 3-1-1 information hotline received over 175,000 calls from concerned residents during the weekend.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Amateur radio operators attached to New York City ARES provided a backup communications link to emergency shelters and hospitals.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Amateur radio repeaters were supplied with emergency power via generators and batteries and remained functional.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Major U.S. networks (CBS, NBC, ABC and Fox) and some cable television channels (HBO, MTV and Nickelodeon), centered in New York City, were unable to broadcast normally, so backup stations and flagship transmitters in Dallas were used for prime-time TV.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] ABC ran their news broadcasts from Washington, D.C. instead.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Much of Manhattan, including the headquarters of the United Nations, was rendered without power, as were all area airports (with the exception of Newburgh's Stewart International Airport, which had once been a military airbase and had its own generators).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] All New York-area rail transportation including the subway, the PATH lines between Manhattan and New Jersey, NJ Transit Rail Operations, Metro-North, and the Long Island Rail Road, were without power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Limited railroad service resumed early Friday morning through the use of diesel trains.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] More than 600 subway and commuter rail cars were trapped between stations.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] New York's Metropolitan Transportation Authority (which operates the subway) and the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey (which operates the PATH lines) reported that all passengers were evacuated without serious injury.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] PATH resumed service on the Uptown Hudson Tubes by 9:45 p.m. that evening; system-wide service resumed at 11 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] By comparison, full service on the New York City Subway system returned gradually from Friday through Saturday morning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Without traffic lights, gridlock was reported as people in Lower and Midtown Manhattan fled their offices on foot.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] For hours into the evening, the streets, highways, bridges and tunnels were jammed with traffic and pedestrians leaving Manhattan.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A number of civilians helped direct traffic.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The normally four-hour bus journey from Manhattan to Washington, D.C. took more than eight hours.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] According to reports, it took four hours just to get out of Manhattan.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Hundreds of people found themselves trapped in elevators at the start of the blackout, requiring urgent response from the FDNY.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] By late evening, the New York City Fire Department had reportedly confirmed that all stalled elevators in approximately 800 Manhattan high-rise office and apartment buildings had been cleared.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Mayor Michael Bloomberg advised residents to open their windows, drink plenty of liquids to avoid heat stroke, and not to forget their pets.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Temperatures were 92 °F (33 °C) with high humidity, as New York had just experienced a record-breaking rain spell that had started at the end of July.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] With cell phone operation mostly stalled by circuit overloads, New Yorkers were lining up 10 deep or more at pay phones as ordinary telephone service remained largely unaffected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A number of people found themselves with no phone service at home.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] While some commuters were able to find alternate sleeping arrangements, a number of people were left stranded in New York and slept in parks and on the steps of public buildings.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] While practically all businesses and retail establishments closed down, multiple bars and pubs reported a brisk business as New Yorkers took the opportunity to spend the evening "enjoying" the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Tourists' hotel rooms were blacked out, except the hallways, and most of the restaurants in lobbies gave out free food to guests.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Since most perishable items were going to spoil anyway, restaurants and citizens simply prepared what they could and served it to anyone who wanted it, leading to vast block parties in multiple New York City neighborhoods.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Any ice cream in frozen storage also had to be quickly served to any and all passers by.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Indigo Girls were scheduled to perform that evening at Central Park SummerStage, and the band took the stage as planned to play one of the only shows in the affected area, using generators that had been filled with fuel that morning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Their performance was not a full-length concert, as they needed to end early to allow all attendees to exit Central Park before dark.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The venue also had bathrooms, and vendors cooking food on propane grills.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Forty thousand police officers and the entire fire department were called in to maintain order.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] At least two fatalities were linked to the use of flames to provide light, and a number of non-fatal fires also resulted from the use of candles.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Affected areas included most of Hudson, Morris, Essex, Union, Passaic, and Bergen counties, including the major cities of Newark, Jersey City and Paterson, although some sections of Newark and East Orange still had power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Small sections of certain towns in Essex, Hudson, and Union counties had power, as did the entire towns of Butler, Kinnelon and Bloomingdale in Morris and Passaic counties which were served by the Butler Electric Company (these 3 towns were also unaffected by the major blackouts of 1965 and 1977).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Power was returned first to the urban areas because of concerns of safety and unrest.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Counties as far south as Cumberland were affected, where power was restored within an hour.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some towns in Bergen County only momentarily lost power, and had wild oscillations in power line voltage, ranging from about 90 V to 135 V every few minutes for an hour.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The day following the blackout, August 15, the New Jersey Turnpike stopped collecting tolls until 9:00 a.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Parts of New London, Hartford, New Haven, Litchfield, and Fairfield counties, from Greenwich to Danbury and Bridgeport were affected, although most of the state had power all evening, aside from a few momentary interruptions that caused computers to reboot.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Metro-North trains stopped and remained on the tracks for hours, until they could be towed to the nearest station.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Generally, most of the state east of Interstate 91, and some places west of I-91, had power during the duration of the blackout, with some of New Haven's eastern suburbs being seen as the easternmost extreme of the effects of the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A local controversy ensued in the days after the blackout, when the federal government ordered power companies to energize the HVDC Cross Sound Cable between New Haven and Long Island.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] This cable had been installed, but not activated due to environment and fishery concerns.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Attorney General of Connecticut (and future U.S.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Senator), Richard Blumenthal, and the Governor of New York, George Pataki, traded insults over the cable.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Connecticut politicians, without regard for public safety, expressed their outrage that the cable was being turned on, since it did not help anyone in Connecticut, as the cable would transport power from Connecticut to Long Island.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A small area of western Massachusetts was affected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Worcester the event was of sufficient magnitude to reboot some computers, while in Springfield the effect of the event was enough to cause the automatic startup of commercial and industrial backup generation facilities.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some areas were subjected to lower-than-normal voltage (as low as 100 volts AC) and brownouts for periods of up to 24 hours.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Boston area was spared from the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] About 2.3 million households and businesses were affected, including almost all of Metro Detroit, Lansing, Ann Arbor, and surrounding communities in southeast Michigan.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The blackout affected three Michigan utilities: Detroit Edison (whose entire system went down), Lansing Board of Water & Light, and a small portion of Consumers Energy's system in the southeastern corner of the state.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Word quickly spread to the surrounding areas without power and people flocked to surrounding areas that still had power, resulting in crowded stores, packed restaurants, booked hotels, and long queues for the gas stations in these towns.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Locales closest to the affected areas in the northern Detroit suburbs that did not lose power included the areas of Oxford and Holly, communities along M-24 and M-15, and into the Lapeer and Flint/Tri-Cities area.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The city limits of Brighton and Howell were unaffected as well, as they received electricity from Consumers Energy via the Genoa-Latson 138 kV line which interconnects Detroit Edison and Consumers Energy.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Television and radio stations were temporarily knocked off the air and water supplies were disrupted in Detroit due to the failure of electric pumps.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Because of the loss of water pressure, all water was required to be boiled before use until August 18.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Several schools, which had planned to begin the school year August 18, were closed until clean water was available.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A planned August 15 concert at Comerica Park featuring Kiss and Aerosmith was postponed until September 7.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] A Marathon Oil refinery in Melvindale, near Detroit, suffered a small explosion from gas buildup, necessitating an evacuation within one mile (1.6 km) around the plant and the closure of Interstate 75.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Officials feared the release of toxic gases.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Heavy rains on August 17, coupled with the lack of sewage pumps, closed other expressways and prompted urban flood warnings.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Untreated sewage flowed into local rivers in Lansing and Metropolitan Detroit as contingency solutions at some sewage treatment plants failed.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the midst of a summer heat wave, Michiganders were deprived of air conditioning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Several people, mostly elderly individuals, had to be treated for symptoms of heat stroke.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the Detroit area, local television stations' news helicopters were told by each station's management to "stay above the cars' headlights" at night, and to not venture into Downtown Detroit (due to the hazard of flying into an unlit skyscraper).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] During the days immediately after the blackout, a number of TV stations were back on the air, with limited resources.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In one case, WXYZ-TV's news anchor was wearing a T-shirt and shorts, as opposed to his normal news suit, and apologized to viewers for the "rather warm conditions" in the station, as they only had one air conditioner and a couple of fans working.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Downriver communities had to contend with basements flooded with sewage-laden water on the weekend immediately after the blackout due to water and sewage pumps offline from a lack of power, much to the general annoyance of residents in the areas.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] News crews of the areas broadcast notices during their coverages of the blackouts to the Downriver residents, explaining why the pumps had shorted out, as well as to limit water usage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] "Most places have water pressure, some have low pressure...some have none, and some even have *negative pressure*.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] That means in the next few hours, people in the downriver communities should expect flooded basements from, so move all your valuables high up and out of the basements," as WDIV-TV warned.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] West Michigan, including the communities of Grand Rapids, Muskegon, and Holland were mostly unaffected, although a large portion was within "seconds" of joining the blackout according to local U.S.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some communities in Southwest Michigan were impacted, being among the most western locations impacted.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Although right across the border from Sault Ste.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Marie, Michigan was unaffected by the outage, as the two cities are not electrically connected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Over 540,000 homes and businesses were without power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Cleveland, water service stopped because the city is supplied by electric pumps and backup electricity was available only on a limited basis.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Water had to be boiled for several days afterwards.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Portions of the cities of Akron, Mansfield, Massillon, Marion, and Ashland were without power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Cleveland declared a curfew on all persons under the age of 18.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] At Cedar Point amusement park in Sandusky, park employees had to help guests walk down the steps of the 205-foot-tall (62 m) Magnum XL-200 roller coaster, which had stopped on the lift hill due to the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Several other guests had to be helped off rides as a result of the blackout.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Toledo, the Mud Hens baseball team postponed the game scheduled for that night.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Some parts of the city were unaffected by the blackout, notably the suburb of Sylvania.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Other surrounding cities like Bowling Green only experienced a brief outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The area affected by the blackout included all Southern Ontario, except Grimsby, Pelham, Niagara Falls and Fort Erie, from Windsor to Ottawa and all the way to the Quebec border, except for the Cornwall area.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Also affected was Northern Ontario, as far north as Attawapiskat and Moosonee on James Bay and west to Marathon on the Lake Superior shoreline.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Communities affected in northern Ontario included Timmins, Cochrane, Sudbury, Kirkland Lake, North Bay, Wawa, and Sault Ste.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Most of Northwestern Ontario (including Thunder Bay) was not affected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Traffic lights, which had no backup power, were all knocked out.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] All intersections were to be considered an all-way stop.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Coupled with the beginning of the evening rush hour, this caused traffic problems.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In multiple major and minor intersections in large cities, such as Ottawa and Toronto, ordinary citizens began directing traffic until police or others relieved them.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Since there were not enough police officers to direct traffic at every intersection during the afternoon rush hour, passing police officers distributed fluorescent jackets to civilians who were directing traffic.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Drivers and pedestrians generally followed the instructions from them, even though they were not police officers.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Ottawa, the federal government was shut down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Parliamentary Precinct and Parliament Hill were evacuated.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Toronto, the Toronto subway and RT and the Toronto streetcar system were shut down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Passengers had to be evacuated from subway trains by walking through the tunnels.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Major Toronto hospitals reported that they had switched to generators and did not experience problems.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The streetcars remained suspended on August 18 and 19, resuming after assurances they would be exempt from any potential rotating blackouts.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Toronto officials asked residents to curtail unnecessary use of water, as pumps were not working and there was only a 24-hour supply.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Entertainment events were canceled for several days.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] English band Radiohead rescheduled a planned August 16 concert in Toronto until the following October 15 due to the power outage.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The opening of the Canadian National Exhibition, scheduled for August 15, was postponed to August 19.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The roof of the Skydome in Toronto remained open in an effort to conserve power until August 21, when a thunderstorm struck.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Large disruptions of truck traffic in northeastern Ontario were reported due to the unavailability of fuel, including the backlog near North Bay.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The tunnel and bridge between Windsor and Detroit were also closed, with the bridge's pillars illuminated by emergency floodlights, as to not pose a shipping and airplane hazard.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] About 140 miners were marooned underground in the Falconbridge mine in Sudbury when the power went out.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Mine officials said they were safe and could be evacuated if necessary, but were not, due to the risks of doing so with no power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] They were safely evacuated by the morning.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Sarnia, a refinery scrubber lost power and released above-normal levels of pollution; residents were advised to close their windows.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] On the evening of August 14, Ontario premier Ernie Eves declared a state of emergency, instructing nonessential personnel not to go to work the next day and that rolling blackouts could occur for weeks.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Residents were asked not to use televisions, washing machines, or air conditioners if possible, and warned that some restored power might go off again.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Although the full state of emergency was lifted the next day, residents were warned that the normal amount of power would not be available for days, and were still asked to reduce power consumption.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] For two days of this recovery period, diversion of water from the Niagara River for hydroelectric generation was increased to the maximum level, normally used only at night and in winter in order to maintain the scenic appearance of Niagara Falls.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The resultant drop in the river level below the falls meant that the Maid of the Mist tour boats could not dock safely, and their operation had to be suspended.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Petro-Canada refinery in Oakville had to perform an emergency shutdown due to the lack of power.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The plant's flare system produced large flames during the shutdown, leading to erroneous reports in the media that there had been a fire in the plant.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Petro Canada lubricants plant in Mississauga experienced a fire one week later while restarting normal operations.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Many Torontonians remember that night as a moment where the community came together: "Without power, residents of Toronto took to the streets to help direct traffic; florists arranged flowers for weddings by candlelight; and convenience stores served customers in the blackness.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The blackout was confined to the northwest portion of the state.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The state's most populated metros of Philadelphia and Pittsburgh were unaffected.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] According to emergency officials in Erie, Crawford, Venango, Clarion, Bradford, Forest and Warren counties, outages lasted into the night, but there were no serious injuries or incidents.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In New York, about 3,000 fire calls were reported, a number of them from people using candles.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Emergency services responded to 80,000 calls for help, more than double the average.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] From 4 p.m. of August 14 to midnight of August 15, there were 60 all-hands or greater alarm fires, caused mostly by candles.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The FDNY answered over 7,500 calls which resulted in the transmission of over 4,000 alarms.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The blackout contributed to almost 100 deaths.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The blackout prompted the federal government of the United States to include reliability provisions in the Energy Policy Act of 2005.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The standards of the North American Electric Reliability Corporation became mandatory for U.S. electricity providers.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the United States, the Bush administration had emphasized the need for changes to the U.S. national energy policy, critical infrastructure protection, and homeland security.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] During the blackout, most systems that would detect unauthorized border crossings, port landings, or detect unauthorized access to a number of vulnerable sites failed.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] There was considerable fear that future blackouts would be exploited for terrorism.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In addition, the failure highlighted the ease with which the power grid could be taken down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The Ontario government fell in a provincial election held in October 2003; power had long been a major issue.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The government may have been hurt by the success of Quebec and Manitoba, which were not affected whereas Ontario was shut down.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The extra publicity given to Ontario's need to import electricity from the United States, mostly due to a decision of the government not to expand the province's power generating capabilities, may also have adversely affected the Conservative government.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Premier Ernie Eves's handling of the crisis was also criticized; he was not heard from until long after Mayor Bloomberg and Governor Pataki had spoken out.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Due to the regular announcements he gave in the days following the blackout, Eves enjoyed a moderate increase in the polls that his party took as a sign of an opportunity to call an election they could win, but they lost instead.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Con Edison retracted its claim that New York City would have power by 1 a.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] That night some areas of Manhattan regained power at approximately 5 a.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] (August 15), the New York City borough of Staten Island regained power around 3 a.m. on August 15, and Niagara Mohawk predicted that the Niagara Falls area would have to wait until 8 a.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the New York City borough of Brooklyn power was not fully restored until around sunset on August 15.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Half of the affected part of Ontario had power by the morning of August 15, though even in areas where it had come back online, some services were still disrupted or running at lower levels.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The last areas to regain power were usually suffering from trouble at local electrical substations that was not directly related to the blackout itself.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] By August 16, power was fully restored in New York and Toronto.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Toronto's subway and streetcars remained out of service until August 18 to prevent the possibility of equipment being stuck in awkward locations if the power was interrupted again.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Power had been mostly restored in Ottawa, though authorities warned of possible additional disruptions and advised conservation as power continued to be restored to other areas.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Ontarians were asked to reduce their electricity use by 50% until all generating stations could be brought back on line.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Four remained out of service on the 19th.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Illuminated billboards were largely dormant for the week following the blackout, and multiple stores had only a portion of their lights on.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Preparations against the possible disruptions threatened by the Year 2000 problem have been credited for the installation of new electrical equipment and systems which allowed for a relatively rapid restoration of power in some areas.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In the United States and Canada, the regional blackout dominated news broadcasts and news headlines beginning August 15.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] U.S. and Canadian television networks pre-empted normal programming in favor of full-time, advertising-free coverage of the unfolding story.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Once terrorism had been conclusively ruled out as a cause, multiple stations switched back to normal programming following an 8:30 p.m.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] National news stations, such as the CBC and CNN, continued to cover the story by inviting politicians and electrical experts to discuss the situation and suggest ways to prevent blackouts.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Internationally, coverage of the story focused on the development of the situation in the New York City metropolitan area.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Ontario, some cities took part in power conservation challenges or events to remind citizens of the blackout, the most well-known event being the Voluntary Blackout Day hosted by the Ontario Power Authority (OPA).
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] During these events, citizens were encouraged to maximize their energy conservation activities.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] Smaller cities such as London, Guelph, Woodstock and Waterloo took part in the challenges annually.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The final Voluntary Blackout Day was held on August 14, 2010, with OPA moving to more year-round energy conservation efforts.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In Toronto, an annual blackout anniversary party has been held on August 14 since 2006.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] The event takes place at a different downtown location each year and typically features a parade, bike rave, fire performances, live music, bonfires, and cookouts.
[src:c-span/2003-north-america-blackout-p02] In 2024, attendance was estimated at 1,500 to 2,000 people.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The **2008 Democratic National Convention** was a quadrennial presidential nominating convention of the Democratic Party where it adopted its national platform and officially nominated its candidates for president and vice president.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The convention was held in Denver, Colorado, from August 25 to 28, 2008, at the Pepsi Center.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Barack Obama from Illinois gave his acceptance speech on August 28 at Invesco Field in what the party called an "Open Convention".
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Denver last hosted the Democratic National Convention in 1908.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama became the party's first nonwhite nominee, and nominee of African descent, for president.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Joe Biden from Delaware was nominated for vice president.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama officially received the nomination for president on August 27, when his former opponent, U.S.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Hillary Clinton of New York, interrupted the official roll call to move that Obama be selected by acclamation.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Biden accepted the nomination for vice president on the same night.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama accepted his nomination the following night in a speech at Invesco Field before a record-setting crowd of 84,000 people in attendance.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Howard Dean presided over the political party in his capacity as Chair of the Democratic National Convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Daughtry served as chief executive of the Democratic National Convention Committee.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Speaker of the House Nancy Pelosi served as permanent chair of the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Sharing in her responsibilities in the convention were three co-chairmen: Kansas Governor Kathleen Sebelius, Texas State Senator Leticia R.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Van de Putte, and Atlanta Mayor Shirley Franklin.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Choosing to hold the convention the day after the Beijing Olympic Games concluded, the Democratic Party convened in Denver in the last week of August, a week before the Republican National Convention in St.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The decision was made, according to the party, to "maximize momentum for our Democratic ticket in the final months of the Presidential election".
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Customarily, the party of the incumbent president holds its convention after the opposing party has held theirs.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic National Committee presented themes for each day of the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The August 26 theme was "Renewing America's Promise" while its August 27 theme was "Securing America's Future".
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The August 28 theme highlights Obama's campaign motto, "Change We Can Believe In".
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Featured speakers crafted their messages to the theme of the day.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] With close delegate counts for Barack Obama and Hillary Clinton, there was early speculation of the first brokered convention in decades.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Democratic National Committee Chair Howard Dean sought to avoid such a circumstance.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition to the possibility of a brokered convention, a dispute over seating delegates from Florida and Michigan led some to compare the year's convention with the 1968 Democratic National Convention, which ended in a divided party and unhappiness over the outcome.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] This speculation ended when Obama was declared the presumptive nominee on June 3, 2008, and Clinton officially announced later that week that she was suspending her campaign and was fully endorsing Obama.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] On February 2, 2007, the Democratic Party published "Call for the 2008 Democratic National Convention," the rules governing the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] There were 3,409.5 pledged delegates, those committed to vote for a particular candidate, selected by primary voters and caucus participants.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] There were about 823.5 unpledged delegates, those free to vote for any candidate, colloquially known as "superdelegates", for a total of about 4,233 delegates, requiring 2,117 votes to constitute a majority of the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The superdelegates consisted of DNC members, Democratic Congress members and Governors, and other prominent Democrats.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The pledged delegates were allocated among the states, the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico, according to two main criteria: 1) proportion of votes each state gave the candidate in the last three presidential elections; and 2) percentage of votes each state has in the Electoral College.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Fixed numbers of delegates were allocated for American Samoa, Guam, the United States Virgin Islands, and Democrats Abroad.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Under the party's *Delegate Selection Rules for the 2008 Democratic National Convention*, delegates were awarded through proportional representation with a minimum threshold of 15% of votes in a state or congressional district to receive delegates.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The delegate population must reflect the state's ethnic distribution, and at least 50% of the delegates must be women.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Along with presumptive presidential nominee Barack Obama, former opponent Hillary Clinton's name was also placed in the roll call vote for nomination.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The *Los Angeles Times* noted that this has occurred before: Jerry Brown's name was entered into the roll call after losing to Bill Clinton in 1992; Jesse Jackson and Gary Hart also had their names added after losing to Walter F.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Mondale in 1984; while Jackson's name was also entered into the roll call after losing to Michael Dukakis in 1988.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In 1980, Senator Ted Kennedy's name was entered into the roll call after losing to Jimmy Carter.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition, Clinton became only the fourth woman to have her name placed in nomination for president at a major party convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Margaret Chase Smith of Maine was placed in nomination at the 1964 Republican National Convention, and U.S.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Shirley Chisholm of New York was placed in nomination at the 1972 Democratic National Convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In 1976, anti-abortionist Ellen McCormack had her name placed in nomination along with Mo Udall, Jimmy Carter and Jerry Brown.) Clinton would have her name placed in nomination for president once more, in 2016, along with Bernie Sanders.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] All votes cast by the delegates will be counted, and that I move Senator Barack Obama of Illinois be selected by this convention by acclamation as the nominee of the Democratic Party for president of the United States." This was done and the verbal roll call vote was halted.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Earlier the same day, Clinton had released her delegates, allowing them to vote for Obama.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Along with the verbal roll call, a paper ballot was taken.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The results were 3,188.5 for Obama and 1,010.5 for Clinton.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] There are an additional 219 votes that were not cast.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, Nashville, New Orleans, New York City, Orlando, Philadelphia, Phoenix, Pittsburgh, Portland, St.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Louis, Sacramento, Salt Lake City, San Antonio, San Diego, San Francisco, Seattle, and Washington, D.C.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Eleven cities originally accepted the invitation to bid for the convention in January 2006: Anaheim, Dallas, Denver, Detroit, Las Vegas, Minneapolis–St.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, New Orleans, New York City, Orlando, Phoenix, and San Antonio.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] A formal request for proposal was mailed to participating cities on February 27 and the deadline for cities to respond was May 19, 2006.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Only three cities submitted final proposals to host the convention: Denver, Minneapolis-St.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] New Orleans had submitted an initial bid, but on July 12, the city dropped out.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The cities were visited by a 10-member Technical Advisory Committee in June 2006.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] On September 27, the Republicans announced they would have their 2008 convention in St.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, removing it from consideration and leaving only Denver and New York as potential hosts.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Despite hard lobbying by New York party boosters, then-Republican Mayor Michael Bloomberg dealt the campaign a major blow when he announced the city lacked the financial means to support a convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Denver was chosen as the host on January 11, 2007, as Democrats looked to make gains in the "Purple West" states of Colorado, Nevada, and New Mexico.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The work to prepare Pepsi Center for the Democratic National Convention was expected to cost $15 million.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition, a 220,000-square-foot (20,000 m2) temporary building to be used by the media was built near Pepsi Center.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Convention organizers, including the Democratic National Convention Committee and the Denver 2008 Convention Host Committee, expected 50,000 attendees, of whom 5,000 were delegates and 15,000 media personnel.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] However, they anticipated 75,000 people coming to watch Obama accept the nomination on Thursday.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The stage erected at Invesco Field for the convention's final evening featured doric columns meant to evoke the White House's neoclassical architecture.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Some critics criticized this design as evoking imperial imagery.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The head of the International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees Local No.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] 7, Jim Taylor, refused to sign a no-strike agreement for the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Pepsi Center normally uses nonunion labor, but used Taylor's union during the convention, and Taylor wanted Pepsi Center to use his union for all events.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] As with past political conventions since 2000, the Democratic National Convention was designated a National Special Security Event (NSSE) by the United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS).
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Denver Police Department doubled in size to 3,000 officers for the DNC, by including other police from 52 neighboring law enforcement agencies.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Police were equipped with riot gear in preparation for unorganized protests.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Throughout the event, a total of 152 arrests were made for offenses related to the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "One Nation," with Michelle Obama as the "headline prime-time speaker." She was introduced by her brother, Craig Robinson.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Also, Maya Soetoro-Ng spoke briefly on growing up with her older brother Barack Obama, and brought an Asian-American presence to the stage for the first time.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] *The Work to Come: A Tribute to Senator Edward Kennedy*, directed and produced by Mark Herzog and Chris Cowen in association with Ken Burns, was introduced by Kennedy's niece, Caroline Kennedy.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Consistent with the theme of the evening, Former Republican congressman Jim Leach gave his public endorsement of Barack Obama.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] His speech was introduced by Senator Tom Harkin, a fellow Iowan.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Kennedy was not expected to attend the convention due to his illness, but nevertheless made a surprise appearance and speech in the evening.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] A video about former President Jimmy Carter's humanitarian work was also shown, followed by a brief appearance by the president himself.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "Renewing America's Promise." Senator Barbara Mikulski was one of several elected women Democrats selected to speak that evening.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Hillary Clinton was the headline prime-time speaker.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Ohio Representative Dennis Kucinich, who had also run as a presidential candidate in the 2008 Democratic Party primaries, gave a spirited speech structured around the refrain "Wake up America!" The speech levies trenchant criticism of the perceived abuses of power of the George W.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Bush administration, attacks the corporate control of the American political and economic systems and rallies for a program of universal health coverage, universal higher education, tax reform, trade policy reform, energy regulation, civil liberties and de-militarization.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] At the end of the speech, Kucinich endorses Barack Obama and Joe Biden for president and vice-president.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] His words electrified the audience who began delivering a standing ovation midway through the speech and continued cheering past its closure.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "Securing America's Future".
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] It featured a speech by Joe Biden, the vice presidential candidate.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Before his speech he was introduced by his oldest son Beau Biden, Delaware's Attorney General.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In that speech Beau talked about how his father would tuck him and his siblings into bed each night after returning home, how he refused invitations to cocktail parties in DC because he did not want to miss his granddaughter (Beau's daughter) Natalie's birthday.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] He remembered the accident that killed his mother and sister and how his father took the Senate oath at his and his brother's bedside.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Several years later his father remarried "their Mom Jill" and their family was rebuilt.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In the end Beau, whose Delaware National Guard unit where he is Captain was to be deployed to Iraq, said that while his father was always there for him, his duties that fall would prevent him from being there for his Dad.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Thus he asked his family and everyone else to be there in November for his father and to be there for Barack Obama and make this country better again.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Other speakers included former president Bill Clinton, 2004 presidential candidate Sen.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] After Joe Biden spoke, his first address as vice presidential nominee, Barack Obama made a surprise appearance praising the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The convention moved to Invesco Field at Mile High, with a DNCC record crowd of more than 84,000 people in attendance.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Speakers included former Vice President Al Gore, Governor of Virginia Tim Kaine, Governor of New Mexico Bill Richardson, Illinois Senator Dick Durbin, and the evening culminated in Barack Obama's acceptance speech.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] More than 38 million people across 10 U.S. cable and broadcast TV networks tuned in to watch.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In his speech, Obama said, "Our government should work for us, not against us.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] It should ensure opportunity, not for just those with the most money and influence, but for every American who is willing to work.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] That's the promise of America, the idea that we are responsible for ourselves, but that we also rise and fall as one nation, the fundamental belief that I am my brother's keeper, I am my sister's keeper.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Florida and Michigan legislatures moved forward their primaries to January 2008, in contravention of party rules and were stripped of their delegates.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Clinton campaign with others initially opposed their seating, stating they acknowledged that the delegates from neither Michigan nor Florida would count.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] However, after winning the Florida and Michigan primaries, Senator Clinton spoke in favor of seating the states' delegates (despite Joe Biden, Barack Obama, Bill Richardson, and John Edwards having removed their names from the Michigan primary ballot).
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] DNC Chair Howard Dean asked Florida and Michigan to submit a new plan for a process to choose the delegates, such as holding primaries again, or let the matter be referred to the Credentials Committee.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In May 2008, the rules committee agreed to let their delegates have half a vote each.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In August 2008, Senator Barack Obama, the party's presumptive nominee, asked the credentials committee to let the two states have full voting rights at the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee met on August 24, the day before the convention began, and voted to restore full voting rights to Florida and Michigan.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] From March through July, convention planners were provided subsidized and untaxed fuel from municipal government gas pumps at a price less than retail fuel available to ordinary citizens, reportedly without a signed contract.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] After the practice became public at a meeting with city council members, only convention planners' buses were allowed to refuel at city facilities.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit on behalf of 12 organizations who planned to protest at the Democratic Convention, requesting that the Secret Service and Denver officials release information about procedures concerning protesting times and the Demonstration Zone.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In a June 12 release, a parade route and Demonstration Zone were announced.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Demonstration Zone will be in Parking Lot A of Pepsi Center.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Some groups, including two groups opposing abortion chose to delay filing suit after it was announced that their applications for permits are being processed.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In an amended complaint, the ACLU and interested advocacy groups have filed suit against the Secret Service and the city and county of Denver, questioning the constitutionality of the restrictions.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The lawsuit failed and the ACLU did not appeal.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The official demonstration zone was unused on Monday afternoon, as the convention opened.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The 47,000-square-foot (4,400 m2) fenced area was 700 feet (210 m) from Pepsi Center and delegates could pass from 8 to 200 feet (61 m) from it.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Denver Police Department claimed the facility was set up to allow those arrested to be processed and released in a more timely manner than they would if they were to be transferred to the Denver County Jail, but faced substantial criticism in mainstream media.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] On August 24, three men were arrested in the Denver, Colorado area on drugs and weapons charges.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Following the arrests of Shawn Robert Adolf, Tharin Robert Gartrell and Nathan Johnson, a possible plot to assassinate Senator Obama surfaced.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Authorities later said they had determined the trio posed no credible danger to Obama; U.S.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] A reporter from ABC News was arrested as he was photographing a meeting of Democratic senators and VIP donors.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The reporter, Asa Eslocker, was arrested by the Denver police and charged with trespassing, interference, and failure to follow a lawful order.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The charges were dismissed by the Denver city attorney.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] On August 26, 2008, a group of anti-abortion activists from American Right to Life Action constructed a sign on Table Mountain outside Denver, overlooking the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The sign, made of 2400 sheets, read "Destroys / uNborn / Children" in three rows; it was lined up so that "DNC" appeared vertically in a different color.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Later that day, the protesters were asked by the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department to remove the sign.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] No citations were issued, though the group did violate two open space regulations of not applying for a special activity permit and going into a restricted and closed area that is considered sensitive to wildlife.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Microsoft was chosen as the web content provider for the convention web site, along with Vertigo Software as the developer.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The video application developed was based on Microsoft's Silverlight platform and provided high-definition video streams.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The choice of technology that required proprietary software from a company with a history of antitrust problems was criticized for both the exclusion of competing platforms by way of Silverlight's proprietary video codec and for requiring visitors to install the software when visiting the site.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Although Moonlight is a cross-platform alternative that attempts to be compatible with Silverlight, as of the time of the convention it did not support features found in version 2 which were required.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] In contrast, the web site for the 2008 Republican National Convention used Adobe Flash streams provided through Ustream.TV and YouTube which are viewable with several applications including the free software cross-platform clone Gnash.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Ava DuVernay was commissioned by the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture to create a film which debuted at the museum's opening on September 24, 2016.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] This film, *August 28: A Day in the Life of a People*, tells of six significant events in African-American history that happened on the same date, August 28.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] The 22-minute film stars Lupita Nyong'o, Don Cheadle, Regina King, David Oyelowo, Angela Bassett, Michael Ealy, Gugu Mbatha-Raw, André Holland and Glynn Turman.
[src:c-span/2008-democratic-national-convention] Events depicted include, among other things, the night Obama accepted the Democratic nomination for president at the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The **2008 Republican National Convention** took place at the Xcel Energy Center (now Grand Casino Arena) in Saint Paul, Minnesota, from September 1, through September 4, 2008.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] This was the latest any major party convention has ever been convened, and the first one to take place entirely in September.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Traditionally, the party who holds the White House has the opportunity to select the date of its convention second, and normally the challenging party holds their convention in July while the incumbent party holds its convention in August.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] This year, later dates were chosen for both conventions because the parties wanted to schedule their conventions after the 2008 Summer Olympics ended.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Bush did not attend the convention (although he did appear by satellite), in order to oversee relief efforts to help citizens recover from Hurricane Gustav.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The attending delegates at the convention nominated Senator John McCain from Arizona for president and Governor Sarah Palin of Alaska for vice president.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] 1,191 pledged delegates were necessary for candidates to win the respective nominations.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The two women appeared together and delivered short remarks to encourage support for hurricane relief efforts.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Four cities made bids to the Republican National Committee (RNC) for proposals to host the 2008 Convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Those cities were Cleveland, Ohio; Minneapolis-Saint Paul, Minnesota; New York City, New York; and Tampa-St.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The RNC Selection Committee made its recommendation for Minneapolis-Saint Paul and on September 27, 2006, the RNC made its decision public that the 2008 Republican National Convention would be held in Minneapolis-Saint Paul.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The RNC made their decision earlier than originally scheduled because the Democratic National Committee (DNC) also had Minneapolis-Saint Paul as a finalist among bidding cities.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] With the landfall of Hurricane Gustav on the U.S.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Gulf Coast, the White House canceled the planned appearances of President Bush and Vice President Dick Cheney.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Governors Bobby Jindal of Louisiana and Rick Perry of Texas skipped the convention to remain in their states during the hurricane's landfall.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The Monday, September 1, 2008, schedule was compressed to two hours from seven.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] McCain called on the party to reduce partisan activities ahead of the hurricane's arrival.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The Republican Party chartered a DC-9 to fly convention delegates representing the affected areas back home to their families.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The last time a major hurricane struck in a Presidential-election year was Hurricane Andrew in 1992, which hit South Florida four days after the Republican Convention in Houston, Texas.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] On March 26, 2008, the NFL and NBC agreed to move the kickoff time of a September 4 season-opening football game to 7:00 p.m.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The game ended relatively on time, at 10:01 p.m.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] EDT, with NBC Sports handing off to NBC News within moments of the end of the game.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] According to Nielsen Media Research, 38.9 million Americans watched McCain deliver his acceptance speech—a half million more than tuned in to see Obama the previous week.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] To be selected as the 2008 Republican Party Nominee, a candidate must have received the vote of 1,191 delegates.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] As of March 4, 2008, McCain had received the pledges of more than 1,191 delegates.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Although most of those delegates were *not* required to vote for him, on September 3, 2008, McCain won the nomination almost unanimously.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Palin was nominated for vice president by voice vote on September 4, 2008.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Approximately 10,000 largely peaceful protesters marched against the war in Iraq and 2,000 more to end homelessness and poverty.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] About 1,000 people in place for the third major march, and the last to be sanctioned, were stopped on Thursday, September 4, 2008, by police because they attempted to begin their march after the time their march permit expired.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The Anti-War Committee, which supports nonviolent action and civil disobedience and had cooperated with anarchist groups, had organized and publicized the march to protest at the time of McCain's acceptance speech, which was in violation of the court-approved protest permit time.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Ron Paul's Campaign for Liberty and 10,000 Ron Paul supporters attended the *Rally for the Republic*, a protest convention on September 2, 2008, held a few miles from the Xcel Energy Center at the Minneapolis Target Center in direct contrast to the Republican National Convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Several groups had been preparing to protest near the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] In early January 2008, protesters marched from the Minnesota State Capitol to the Xcel Energy Center in hopes of securing a protest permit.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The Saint Paul Police Department authorized the event, but only approved the permit through July 2008.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] On February 8 and February 9, 2008, antiwar protesters attended a weekend conference at the University of Minnesota to discuss the protests and antiwar rally.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] On February 28, 2008, the Associated Press (AP) reported that the police department adopted new guidelines for the investigation of protest groups.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The police department said that this did not have anything to do with the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] In early March 2008, the city of Saint Paul gave the first permits to protest organizers.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The city had said that it was not going to follow the "New York model" for protest security, referring to the tactics the New York City Police Department used for the 2004 Republican National Convention protest activity.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Later, on March 24, 2008, the antiwar group the *Coalition to March on the RNC and Stop the War*, sued the city, claiming their free speech and due process rights were denied by the vagueness of the permits which did not specify a permitted route for their march.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] On July 16, 2008, a Federal judge upheld the terms of the permit.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] And when the time came on September 2, 2008, police led the Poor People's Economic Human Rights Campaign for two hours on a 2.5 miles (4.0 km) trek away from the convention which had been less than 1 mile (1.6 km) from their starting point.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Before the convention began, search warrants were executed by Ramsey County Sheriff Bob Fletcher in coordination with the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Six persons who were a part of the organizing group, the RNC Welcoming Committee, were arrested when police executed search warrants on a handful of homes in Minneapolis and Saint Paul during the weekend preceding the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Media outlets reported on several of the searches.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Given the nature of the probable cause for the warrant applications, a district court judge authorized no-knock warrants.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Police entered the homes wearing body armor with weapons drawn, which is standard for no-knock warrants.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] RNC Welcoming Committee members detained at the group's headquarters, located in an old theater on Saint Paul's West Side, were ultimately arrested by Ramsey County Sheriff Bob Fletcher of misdemeanor fire code violations.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] On the first day of the convention, a group of protesters stood in front of approximately 30 to 40 delegates from Connecticut in an attempt to prevent them from entering the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Paramedics had to treat an 83-year-old member of the delegation for breathing problems when his credentials were ripped from his neck by a protester.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Additionally, a black bloc smashed windows of downtown businesses and slashed the tires several police cars, lit one police car on fire, and used a garbage dumpster as a battering ram against another.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] During the convention's first three days, more than 300 individuals were detained by police, including journalists, healthcare workers, and legal observers.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Some were released, but nearly half received felony charges.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Of these felony arrests, many cases were dropped or reviewed, sometimes for lesser charges, and about 21 were found to be prosecutable.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] About 102 persons were arrested for unlawful assembly at a Rage Against the Machine concert in downtown Minneapolis.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Over the four days of the convention, more than 30 journalists were arrested while reporting on the protests.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The arrests included journalists from national organizations such as AP and *Democracy Now!*, journalists from local radio and TV stations, as well as university journalism students and advisors.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Three journalists from *Democracy Now!*—including principal host Amy Goodman—were detained by police during their reporting on the protests.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] According to a press release by *Democracy Now!*, Goodman was arrested after confronting officers regarding the arrest of her colleagues.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The officers were in the midst of crowd control, and ordered Goodman to move back.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] She was arrested after refusing the officer's orders.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] All were held on charges of "probable cause for riot".
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Several news sources have criticized the arrest as unlawful and a violation of the freedom of the press, and warned of the "chilling effects" of such measures.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Democracy Now! journalist Amy Goodman and producers Sharif Abdel Kouddous and Nicole Salazar prevailed in a lawsuit against the cities of Minneapolis and St.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Secret Service brought by the Center for Constitutional Rights, attorney Steven Reiss from Weil, Gotshal & Manges LLP in New York, and Albert Goins of Minneapolis.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The federal lawsuit asserted that the government cannot, in the name of security, limit the flow of information by intimidating and arresting journalists who engage in constitutionally protected reporting on speech protected by the First Amendment, such as dissent or law enforcement activities.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The settlement included compensation of $100,000 for the three journalists and an agreement by the St.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] The final protest march was permitted for 2:00 to 5:00 p.m. on the final day of the convention.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] This meant that the last of the marchers needed to be back on capitol grounds by 5 p.m.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] By 4 p.m., the march had still not left the capitol grounds.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Understanding that the protesters were interested in being near the Xcel Energy Center when delegates were, police offered a compromise: march leaders were told that if they started their march before 5 p.m., police would allow it to continue past the permit time.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] When the final protest march permit expired at 5 p.m., overpasses over Interstate 94 leading into downtown from the state capitol were closed.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] This march would have been in violation of the court-approved march permits.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Between 300 and 400 people were arrested or held including 19 journalists, among them AP reporters Amy Forliti and Jon Krawczynski, reporters from *Twin Cities Daily Planet* and *The Uptake*, and Paul Demko of *The Minnesota Independent*.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Total arrests of convention protesters numbered approximately 800, although only 15 cases resulted in criminal charges.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] District Court, claiming civil rights abuses by the St.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Paul Police Department and other agencies involved in the RNC, particularly the Minneapolis Police Department and Ramsey County Sheriff's Office.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Search warrants were still being granted into 2009 in relation to the events that transpired during the 2008 RNC.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Both McKay and Crowder were arrested based on FBI surveillance and testimony by former-activist turned informant, Brandon Michael Darby and Andrew C.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Darst, also known as "Panda," "warchyld" or Killswitch.
[src:c-span/2008-republican-national-convention] Darst is currently being charged in Ramsey County, MN, with two felony counts of first- and second-degree burglary as well as fifth-degree assault relating to a January 11, 2009, domestic disturbance.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The **2011 Egyptian revolution**, also known as the **25 January Revolution** (Arabic: ثورة ٢٥ يناير, romanized: *Thawrat khamsa wa-ʿišrūn yanāyir*), began on 25 January 2011 and spread across Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The date was set by various youth groups to coincide with National Police Day as a statement against increasing police brutality during the later years of Hosni Mubarak's presidency.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] It consisted of demonstrations, marches, occupations of plazas, non-violent civil resistance, acts of civil disobedience and strikes.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Millions of protesters from a range of socio-economic and religious backgrounds demanded Mubarak's removal from the office of president of Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Violent clashes between security forces and protesters resulted in at least 846 people killed and over 6,000 injured.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Protesters retaliated by burning over 90 police stations across the country.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Egyptian protesters' grievances focused on legal and political issues, including police brutality, state-of-emergency laws, lack of political freedom, civil liberty, freedom of speech, corruption, high unemployment, food-price inflation and low wages.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The protesters' primary demands were the end of the Mubarak regime.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Strikes by labour unions added to the pressure on government officials.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the uprising, the capital, Cairo, was described as "a war zone" and the port city of Suez saw frequent violent clashes.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Protesters defied a government-imposed curfew, which the police and military could not enforce in any case.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Egypt's Central Security Forces, loyal to Mubarak, were gradually replaced by military troops.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In the chaos, there was looting by rioters which was instigated (according to opposition sources) by plainclothes police officers.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In response, watch groups were organised by civilian vigilantes to protect their neighborhoods.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 11 February 2011, Vice President Omar Suleiman announced that Mubarak resigned as president, turning power over to the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces (SCAF).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The military junta, chaired by defense minister Muhammad Hussein Tantawy, announced on 13 February that the constitution was suspended, both houses of parliament dissolved and the military would govern for six months (until elections could be held).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The previous cabinet, including Prime Minister Ahmed Shafik, would serve as a caretaker government until a new one was formed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] However, the Morsi government encountered fierce opposition after his attempt to pass an Islamic-leaning constitution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Morsi also issued a temporary presidential decree that raised his decisions over judicial review to enable the passing of the constitution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] It sparked general outrage from secularists and members of the military, and a revolution broke out against his rule on 28 June 2013.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 3 July 2013, Morsi was deposed by the minister of defence, General Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, as millions of Egyptians took to the streets in support of early elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Sisi went on to become Egypt's president after an election in 2014 which was boycotted by opposition parties.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Hosni Mubarak became President of Egypt after the assassination of Anwar Sadat in 1981.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] He inherited an authoritarian system from Sadat which was imposed in 1952 following the coup against King Farouk.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The coup in 1952 led to the abolishment of the monarchy and Egypt became a military dominated one-party state.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Gamal Abdel Nasser, who was a member of the Free Officers, became the second President of Egypt following the resignation of Muhammad Naguib, and under his rule, the Arab Socialist Union operated as the sole political party in Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Under Sadat, the multi-party system during the monarchy was reintroduced but the National Democratic Party (which evolved from Nasser’s Arab Socialist Union) remained dominant in Egypt’s politics and there were restrictions on opposition parties.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mubarak's National Democratic Party (NDP) maintained one-party rule.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] His government received support from the West and aid from the United States by its suppression of Islamic militants and maintaining the peace treaty with Israel.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mubarak was often compared to an Egyptian pharaoh by the media and some critics due to his authoritarian rule.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] He was in the 30th year of his regime when the 2011 uprising began.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] According to political economist Adam Hanieh (2011), Mubarak's rule further deepened neoliberal reforms under Sadat creating close alliances between state institutions and business elites.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] These continued reforms intensified wealth disparities and fostered widespread corruption.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Similarly, Angela Joya (2011) links two decades of privatization and corruption to rising youth unemployment and inequality, which spurred waves of labour protests in industrial centres like Mahalla al-Kubra in the early 2000s.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The clear economic and social grievances became key sources of political mobilization leading up to the 2011 uprising.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Most causes of the revolution against Mubarak—inherited power, corruption, under-development, unemployment, unfair distribution of wealth and the presence of Israel—also existed in 1952, when the Free Officers ousted King Farouk.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A new cause of the 2011 revolution was the increase in population, which aggravated unemployment.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During his presidency, Anwar Sadat neglected the modernisation of Egypt in contrast to his predecessor, Gamal Abdel Nasser, and his cronyism cost the country infrastructure industries which could generate new jobs.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Communications media such as the internet, cell phones and satellite TV channels augmented mosques and Friday prayers, traditional means of mass communication.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The mosques brought the Muslim Brotherhood to power, and the Brotherhood pressured all governments from 1928 through 2011 (as it had also done in neighbouring countries).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mubarak's younger son, Gamal Mubarak, was rumoured in 2000 to succeed his father as the next president of Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Gamal began receiving attention from the Egyptian media, since there were apparently no other heirs to the presidency.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Bashar al-Assad's rise to power in Syria in June 2000, after the death of his father Hafez, sparked debate in the Egyptian press about the prospects for a similar scenario in Cairo.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the years after Mubarak's 2005 re-election, several left- and right-wing (primarily unofficial) political groups expressed opposition to the inheritance of power, demanded reforms and asked for a multi-candidate election.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In 2006, with opposition increasing, *Daily News Egypt* reported an online campaign initiative (the National Initiative against Power Inheritance) demanding that Gamal reduce his power.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The campaign said that "President Mubarak and his son constantly denied even the possibility of [succession].
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the decade, public perception that Gamal would succeed his father grew.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] He wielded increasing power as NDP deputy secretary general and chair of the party's policy committee.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Analysts described Mubarak's last decade in power as "the age of Gamal Mubarak".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] With his father's health declining and no appointed vice-president, Gamal was considered Egypt's *de facto* president by some.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Although Gamal and his father denied an inheritance of power, he was speculated as likely to be chosen as the NDP candidate in the presidential election scheduled for 2011, when Hosni Mubarak's presidential term was set to expire.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Gamal ultimately declined to run following the 2011 protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Egypt was under a state of emergency since the assassination of Sadat in 1981, pursuant to Law No.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A previous state of emergency was enacted in the 1967 Six-Day War before being lifted in 1980.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Police powers were extended, constitutional rights and *habeas corpus* were effectively suspended and censorship was legalised as a result.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The emergency law limited non-governmental political activity, including demonstrations, unapproved political organisations and unregistered financial donations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Mubarak government cited the threat of terrorism in extending the state of emergency, claiming that opposition groups such as the Muslim Brotherhood could gain power in Egypt if the government did not forge parliamentary elections and suppress the group through emergency law.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] This led to the imprisonment of activists without trial, illegal, undocumented and hidden detention facilities and the rejection of university, mosque and newspaper staff based on their political affiliation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A December 2010 parliamentary election was preceded by a media crackdown, arrests, candidate bans (particularly Muslim Brotherhood candidates) and allegations of fraud due to the near-unanimous victory by the NDP in parliament.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Human rights organizations estimated that in 2010, between 5,000 and 10,000 people were in long-term detention without charge or trial.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] According to a US Embassy report, police brutality had been widespread in Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In the five years before the revolution, the Mubarak regime denied the existence of torture or abuse by police.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] However, claims by domestic and international groups provided cellphone videos or first-hand accounts of hundreds of cases of police brutality.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Egyptian Organization for Human Rights documented 30 cases of torture during the year 2009.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In numerous trials defendants alleged that police tortured them during questioning.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the year activists and observers circulated some amateur cellphone videos documenting the alleged abuse of citizens by security officials.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] For example, on 8 February, a blogger posted a video of two police officers, identified by their first names and last initials, sodomizing a bound naked man named Ahmed Abdel Fattah Ali with a bottle.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 12 August, the same blogger posted two videos of alleged police torture of a man in a Port Said police station by the head of investigations, Mohammed Abu Ghazala.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The deployment of Baltageya (Arabic: بلطجية)—plainclothes agitators—by the NDP was a hallmark of the Mubarak government.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Egyptian Organisation for Human Rights documented 567 cases of torture, including 167 deaths, by police from 1993 to 2007.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Excessive force was often used by law enforcement agencies against popular uprisings.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 6 June 2010, a twenty-eight-year-old Egyptian, Khaled Mohamed Saeed, died under disputed circumstances in the Sidi Gaber area of Alexandria, with witnesses testifying that he was beaten to death by police – an event which galvanised Egyptians around the issue of police brutality.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Authorities stated that Khaled died choking on hashish while being chased by police officers.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Pictures which were released of Khaled's disfigured corpse from the morgue showed signs of torture.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A Facebook page, "We are all Khaled Said", helped attract nationwide attention to the case.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mohamed ElBaradei, former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, led a 2010 rally in Alexandria against police abuse, and visited Saeed's family to offer condolences.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the January–February 2011 protests, police brutality was common.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Jack Shenker, a reporter for *The Guardian*, was arrested during the Cairo protests on 26 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] He witnessed fellow Egyptian protesters being tortured, assaulted, and taken to undisclosed locations by police officers.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Shenker and other detainees were released after covert intervention by Ayman Nour, the father of a fellow detainee.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Corruption, coercion not to vote and manipulation of election results occurred during many elections over Mubarak's 30-year rule.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Until 2005, Mubarak was the only presidential candidate (with a yes-or-no vote).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mubarak won five consecutive presidential elections with a sweeping majority.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Although opposition groups and international election-monitoring agencies charged that the elections were rigged, those agencies were not allowed to monitor elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The only opposition presidential candidate in recent Egyptian history, Ayman Nour, was imprisoned before the 2005 elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] According to a 2007 UN survey, voter turnout was extremely low (about 25 per cent) because of a lack of trust in the political system.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The vast majority of Egyptians live near the banks of the Nile, in an area of about 40,000 square kilometers (15,000 sq mi) where the only arable land is found.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In late 2010, about 40 per cent of Egypt's population lived on the equivalent of roughly US$2 per day, with a large portion relying on subsidised goods.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Egypt's economy was highly centralised during the presidency of Gamal Abdel Nasser, becoming more market-driven under Anwar Sadat and Mubarak.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] From 2004 to 2008 the Mubarak government pursued economic reform to attract foreign investment and increase GDP, later postponing further reforms because of the Great Recession.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The international economic downturn slowed Egypt's GDP growth to 4.5 per cent in 2009.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In 2010, analysts said that the government of Prime Minister Ahmed Nazif would need to resume economic reform to attract foreign investment, increase growth and improve economic conditions.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Despite recent high national economic growth, living conditions for the average Egyptian remained relatively poor (albeit better than other African nations with no significant social upheavals).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Political corruption in the Mubarak administration's Interior Ministry rose dramatically, due to increased control of the system necessary to sustain his presidency.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The rise to power of powerful businessmen in the NDP, the government and the House of Representatives led to public anger during the Ahmed Nazif government.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Ahmed Ezz monopolised the steel industry, with more than 60 per cent of market share.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Aladdin Elaasar, an Egyptian biographer and American professor, estimated that the Mubarak family was worth from $50 to $70 billion.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the 2010 elections, opposition groups complained about government harassment and fraud.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Opposition and citizen activists called for changes to a number of legal and constitutional provisions affecting elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In 2010, Transparency International's Corruption Perceptions Index (CPI) gave Egypt a score of 3.1 based on perceptions by business people and analysts of the degree of corruption (with 10 being clean, and 0 totally corrupt).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] To prepare for the possible overthrow of Mubarak, opposition groups studied Gene Sharp's work on nonviolent action and worked with leaders of Otpor, the student-led Serbian organisation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Copies of Sharp's list of 198 non-violent "weapons", translated into Arabic and not always attributed to him, were circulated in Tahrir Square during its occupation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Following the ousting of Tunisian president Zine El Abidine Ben Ali after mass protests, many analysts (including former European Commission President Romano Prodi) saw Egypt as the next country where such a revolution might occur.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] After the self-immolation of Mohamed Bouazizi in Tunisia on 17 December, a man set himself on fire on 18 January in front of the Egyptian parliament and five more attempts followed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 17 January, Abdou Abdel Monaam, a baker, also set himself on fire to protest a law that prevented restaurant owners from buying subsidised bread, leading him to buy bread at the regular price – which is five times higher than the subsidised.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mohammed Farouq Mohammed, who is a lawyer, also set himself alight in front of the parliament to protest his ex-wife, who did not allow him to see his daughters.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In Alexandria, an unemployed man by the name of Ahmed Hashem Sayed also set himself on fire.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Opposition groups planned a day of revolt for 25 January, coinciding with National Police Day, to protest police brutality in front of the Ministry of Interior.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Protesters also demanded the resignation of the Minister of Interior, an end to State corruption, the end of emergency law and presidential term limits for the president.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Many political movements, opposition parties and public figures supported the day of revolt, including Youth for Justice and Freedom, the Coalition of the Youth of the Revolution, the Popular Democratic Movement for Change, the Revolutionary Socialists and the National Association for Change.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The April 6 Youth Movement was a major supporter of the protest, distributing 20,000 leaflets saying "I will protest on 25 January for my rights".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Ghad El-Thawra Party, Karama, Wafd and Democratic Front supported the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest opposition group, confirmed on 23 January that it would participate.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Public figures, including novelist Alaa Al Aswany, writer Belal Fadl and actors Amr Waked and Khaled Aboul Naga, announced that they would participate.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The leftist National Progressive Unionist Party (the *Tagammu*) said that it would not participate, and the Coptic Church urged Christians not to participate in the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Twenty-six-year-old Asmaa Mahfouz was instrumental in sparking the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In a video blog posted a week before National Police Day, she urged the Egyptian people to join her on 25 January in Tahrir Square to bring down the Mubarak regime.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mahfouz's use of video blogging and social media went viral and urged people not to be afraid.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The Facebook group for the event attracted 80,000 people.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 22 November 2012, Morsi issued a declaration immunizing his decrees from challenge and attempting to protect the work of the constituent assembly drafting the new constitution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The declaration required a retrial of those acquitted of killing protesters, and extended the constituent assembly's mandate by two months.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The declaration also authorised Morsi to take any measures necessary to protect the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Liberal and secular groups walked out of the constituent assembly because they believed that it would impose strict Islamism, while the Muslim Brotherhood supported Morsi.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Morsi's declaration was criticised by Constitution Party leader Mohamed ElBaradei (who said that he had "usurped all state powers and appointed himself Egypt's new pharaoh"), and led to violent protests throughout the country.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Protesters again erected tents in Tahrir Square, demanding a reversal of the declaration and the dissolving of the constituent assembly.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A "huge protest" was planned for Tuesday, 27 November, with clashes reported between protesters and police.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The declaration was also condemned by Amnesty International UK.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In April 2013 a youth group was created opposing Morsi and attempting to collect 22 million signatures by 30 June 2013 (the first anniversary of his presidency) on a petition demanding early presidential elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Although protests were scheduled for 30 June, opponents began gathering on the 28th.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Morsi supporters (primarily from Islamic parties) also protested that day.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 30 June the group organised large protests in Tahrir Square and the presidential palace demanding early presidential elections, which later spread to other governorates.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 30 June 2013, the first anniversary of Morsi's inauguration as president, millions of Egyptians protested against him, demanding he step down from office.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A 48-hour ultimatum was issued to him, demanding that he respond to the demands of the Egyptians, and on 3 July 2013, the President of Egypt was overthrown.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Unlike the imposition of martial law which followed the 2011 resignation of Hosni Mubarak, on 4 July 2013, a civilian senior jurist Adly Mansour was appointed interim president and was sworn in over the new government following Morsi's removal.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Mansour had the right to issue constitutional declarations and vested executive power in the Supreme Constitutional Court, giving him executive, judicial and constitutional power.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Morsi refused to accept his removal from office, and many supporters vowed to reinstate him.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] They originally intended their sit-ins to celebrate Morsi's first anniversary, but they quickly became opposed to the new authorities.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Their sit-ins were dispersed on 14 August by security forces, leading to at least 904 civilian deaths and 8 police officers killed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 18 January 2014, the interim government institutionalised a new constitution following a referendum in which 98.2% of voters were supportive.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Participation was low with only 38.6% of registered voters participating although this was higher than the 33% who voted in a referendum during Morsi's tenure.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 26 March 2014, Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, the head of the Egyptian Armed Forces, who at this time was in control of the country, resigned from the military, announcing he would stand as a candidate in the 2014 presidential election.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The poll, which had a 47% turnout, and was held between 26 and 28 May 2014, resulted in a resounding victory for Sisi, who was then sworn into office as President of Egypt on 8 June 2014.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Cairo has been at the centre of the revolution; the largest protests were held in downtown Tahrir Square, considered the "protest movement's beating heart and most effective symbol".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the first three days of the protests there were clashes between the central security police and demonstrators, but on 28 January the police withdrew from all of Cairo.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Citizens formed neighbourhood-watch groups to maintain order, and widespread looting was reported.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Traffic police were reintroduced to Cairo the morning of 31 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Media reports initially claimed that up to one million protesters gathered in the square, leading to widespread coverage of the massive turnout.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] However, other analyses suggested that such estimates might have been overstated.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A crowd-size analysis based on Tahrir Square's physical dimensions and density pointed to smaller numbers, suggesting a maximum capacity of 200,000 to 250,000 people within the square and surrounding areas.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] During the protests, reporters Natasha Smith, Lara Logan and Mona Eltahawy were sexually assaulted while covering the events.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Alexandria, home of Khaled Saeed, experienced major protests and clashes with police.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] There were few confrontations between demonstrators, since there were few Mubarak supporters (except for a few police-escorted convoys).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The breakdown of law and order, including the general absence of police from the streets, continued until the evening of 3 February.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Alexandria's protests were notable for the joint presence of Christians and Muslims in the events following the church bombing on 1 January, which sparked protests against the Mubarak regime.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] In the northern city of Mansoura, there were daily protests against the Mubarak regime beginning on 25 January; two days later, the city was called a "war zone".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 28 January, 13 were reported dead in violent clashes; on 9 February, 18 more protesters died.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] One protest, on 1 February, had an estimated attendance of one million.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The remote city of Siwa had been relatively calm, but local sheikhs reportedly in control put the community under lockdown after a nearby town was burned.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Eyewitness reports suggested that the death toll was high, although confirmation was difficult due to a ban on media coverage in the area.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Some online activists called Suez Egypt's Sidi Bouzid (the Tunisian city where protests began).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] On 3 February, 4,000 protesters took to the streets to demand Mubarak's resignation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] A labour strike took place on 8 February, and large protests were held on 11 February.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The MENA news agency reported the death of two protestors and one police officers on 26 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Over 100,000 protesters gathered on 27 January in front of the city council in Zagazig.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Bedouins in the Sinai Peninsula fought security forces for several weeks.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] As a result of the decreased military border presence, Bedouin groups protected the borders and pledged their support of the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] However, despite mounting tension among tourists no protests or civil unrest occurred in Sharm-El-Sheikh.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Before the protests six cases of self-immolation were reported, including a man arrested while trying to set himself afire in downtown Cairo.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The cases were inspired by (and began one month after) the acts of self-immolation in Tunisia which triggered the Tunisian revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The self-immolators included Abdou Abdel-Moneim Jaafar, Mohammed Farouk Hassan, Mohammed Ashour Sorour and Ahmed Hashim al-Sayyed, who later died from his injuries.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] As of 30 January, Al Jazeera reported as many as 150 deaths in the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] By 29 January, 2,000 people were confirmed injured.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] That day, an employee of the Azerbaijani embassy in Cairo was killed on their way home from work; the following day, Azerbaijan sent a plane to evacuate citizens and opened a criminal investigation into the killing.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Funerals for those killed during the "Friday of Anger" were held on 30 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] Hundreds of mourners gathered, calling for Mubarak's removal.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] By 1 February the protests left at least 125 people dead, although Human Rights Watch said that UN High Commissioner for Human Rights Navi Pillay claimed that as many as 300 might have died in the unrest.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] The unconfirmed tally included 80 Human-Rights-Watch-verified deaths at two Cairo hospitals, 36 in Alexandria and 13 in Suez; over 3,000 people were reported injured.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] An Egyptian governmental fact-finding commission about the revolution announced on 19 April that at least 846 Egyptians died in the nearly three-week-long uprising.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] One prominent Egyptian who was killed was Emad Effat, a senior cleric at the Dar al-Ifta al-Misriyyah school of Al-Azhar University.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] He died 16 December 2011, after he was shot in front of the cabinet building.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p01] At Effat's funeral the following day, hundreds of mourners chanted "Down with military rule".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] International response to the protests was initially mixed, although most governments called for peaceful action on both sides and a move towards reform.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Most Western nations expressed concern about the situation, and many governments issued travel advisories and attempted to evacuate their citizens from Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Joe Hoover (2011), a political analyst, argued that U.S. policy toward the protests reflected the rift between pro-democracy rhetoric and its long-standing realist goal of stability in the region.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Washington initially hesitated to support the removal of Mubarak, fearing that rapid change could jeopardize its security partnerships and peace treaties in the region.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Hoover claims that the Obama Administration's cautious statements, combined with the eventual call for a "peaceful transition," revealed the limits of the U.S. democracy promotion agenda when compared to maintaining influence and counter-terrorism cooperation in the Middle East.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many states in the region expressed concern and supported Mubarak; Saudi Arabia issued a statement "strongly condemn[ing]" the protests, while Tunisia and Iran supported them.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Israel was cautious, with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu asking his government ministers to maintain silence and urging Israel's allies to curb their criticism of President Mubarak; however, an Arab-Israeli parliamentarian supported the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Solidarity demonstrations for the protesters were held worldwide.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Chinese state media framed the Egyptian protests through the lens of securitization, according to Joobani and Helmy (2016).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The government portrayed the mass mobilization displayed during the protests as a source of disorder and foreign interference.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This aligned with China's policy of discouraging similar descent at home while maintaining its own stability for its citizens.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The media emphasized chaos and uncertainty over the real goal of democratization.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Chinese outlets attempted to sway public opinion away from large-scale protests and to present the authoritarian government as a safeguard for national security.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Non-governmental organizations expressed concern about the protests and the heavy-handed state response, with Amnesty International describing attempts to discourage the protests as "unacceptable".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many countries (including the US, Israel, the UK and Japan) issued travel warnings or began evacuating their citizens, and multinational corporations began evacuating expatriate employees.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many university students were also evacuated.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many nations, leaders and organizations hailed the end of the Mubarak regime, and celebrations were held in Tunisia and Lebanon.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] World leaders, including German Chancellor Angela Merkel and UK Prime Minister David Cameron, joined in praising the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] US President Barack Obama praised the achievement of the Egyptian people and encouraged other activists, saying "Let's look at Egypt's example".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Amid growing concern for the country, Cameron was the first world leader to visit Egypt, ten days after Mubarak's resignation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] A news blackout was lifted as the prime minister landed in Cairo for a brief five-hour stopover, hastily added to the beginning of a planned tour of the Middle East.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 15 March, United States Secretary of State Hillary Clinton visited Egypt; she was the highest-ranking US official to visit the country since the handover of power from Mubarak to the military.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Clinton urged military leaders to begin the process of a democratic transition, offering support to protesters and reaffirming ties between the two nations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 29 January, Mubarak indicated that he would change the government because, despite the crossing of a "point of no return", national stability and law and order must prevail.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] He asked the government, formed only months ago, to step down and promised that a new government would be formed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Mubarak appointed Omar Suleiman, head of Egyptian Intelligence, vice president and Ahmed Shafik prime minister.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 1 February, he said he would stay in office until the next election in September, and then leave.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Mubarak promised political reform, but made no offer to resign.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The Muslim Brotherhood joined the revolution on 30 January, calling on the military to intervene and all opposition groups to unite against Mubarak.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] It joined other opposition groups in electing Mohamed el Baradei to lead an interim government.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many of the Al-Azhar imams joined protesters throughout the country on 30 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Christian leaders asked their congregations not to participate in the demonstrations, although a number of young Christian activists joined protests led by New Wafd Party member Raymond Lakah.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 31 January, Mubarak swore in his new cabinet in the hope that the unrest would fade.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Protesters in Tahrir Square continued demanding his ouster, since a vice-president and prime minister were already appointed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] He told the new government to preserve subsidies, control inflation and provide more jobs.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 1 February, Mubarak said that although his candidacy had been announced by high-ranking members of his National Democratic Party, he never intended to run for reelection in September.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Opposition groups, including the Muslim Brotherhood (MB), repeated their demand that Mubarak resign; after the protests turned violent, the MB said that it was time for military intervention.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] ElBaradei formed a "steering committee".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 5 February, talks began between the government and opposition groups for a transitional period before elections.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Scholars have noted that the broad coalition which formed during the uprising began to fragment shortly after Mubarak stepped down.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Political Scientist Benjamin Abrams (2024) describes the fragment as "movement split," where revolutionary alliances split into different factions after the initial goal had been completed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In the Egyptian Revolution, the conservative faction was satisfied with the removal of Mubarak and was focused on restoring stability, while the more radical groups pushed for more extensive reform to the existing political, economic, and social systems.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The split factions made it difficult to produce a unified negotiating position during the transition period.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The loss of unity made it difficult for the coalition to challenge the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces (SCAF), ultimately leading to the rise of military authority in the months following the uprising.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Building on this perspective, political scientist Mostafa Shehata (2018) dives into the post-revolution fragmentation between political factions and their inability to form a unified front.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] According to Shehata, opposition parties and new movements faced distrust, competition, and weak internal structures, which hindered the democratic front's success.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The incomplete organization of party politics, combined with an absence of coordination between revolutionary actors, explains why early democratic gains were quickly undermined during the transition.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This disorganization made it easier for the previously mentioned Supreme Council of the Armed Forces to reemerge in power, embracing authoritarian ideals.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The government cracked down on the media, halting internet access (a primary means of opposition communication) with the help of London-based Vodafone.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Journalists were harassed by supporters of the regime, eliciting condemnation from the Committee to Protect Journalists, European countries and the United States.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Narus, a subsidiary of Boeing, sold the Mubarak government surveillance equipment to help identify dissidents.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The revolution's primary demands, chanted at every protest, were bread (also jobs and other material needs), freedom, social justice and human dignity.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The fulfillment of these demands has been uneven and debatable.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 17 February, an Egyptian prosecutor ordered the detention of three former ministers (interior minister Habib el-Adli, tourism minister Zuhair Garana and housing minister Ahmed el-Maghrabi) and steel magnate Ahmed Ezz pending trial for wasting public funds.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The public prosecutor froze the bank accounts of Adli and his family following accusations that over E£4 million ($680,000) were transferred to his personal account by a businessman.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The foreign minister was requested to contact European countries to freeze the other defendants' accounts.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] That day, the United States announced that it would give Egypt $150 million in aid to help it transition towards democracy.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said that William J.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Burns (undersecretary of state for political affairs) and David Lipton (a senior White House adviser on international economics) would travel to Egypt the following week.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 19 February a moderate Islamic party which had been banned for 15 years, Al-Wasat Al-Jadid (Arabic: حزب الوسط الجديد, New Center Party), was finally recognised by an Egyptian court.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The party was founded in 1996 by activists who split from the Muslim Brotherhood and sought to create a tolerant, liberal Islamic movement, but its four attempts to register as an official party were rejected.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] That day, Prime Minister Ahmed Shafiq also said that 222 political prisoners would be released.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Shafiq said that only a few were detained during the uprising; he put the number of remaining political prisoners at 487, but did not say when they would be released.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 20 February Yehia El Gamal, an activist and law professor, accepted on television the position of deputy prime minister.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The next day, the Muslim Brotherhood announced that it would form a political party, the Freedom and Justice Party led by Saad Ketatni, for the upcoming parliamentary election.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 3 March, Prime Minister Shafiq submitted his resignation to the Supreme Council of the Armed Forces.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The SCAF appointed Essam Sharaf, a former transportation minister and a vocal critic of the regime following his resignation after the 2006 Qalyoub rail accident, to replace Shafik and form a new government.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Sharaf's appointment was seen as a concession to protesters, since he was actively involved in the events in Tahrir Square.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Sharaf appointed former International Court of Justice judge Nabil Elaraby foreign minister and Mansour El Essawi as interior minister.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 16 April the Higher Administrative Court dissolved the former ruling National Democratic Party (NDP), ordering its funds and property to be transferred to the government.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 24 May it was announced that Hosni Mubarak and his sons, Gamal and Alaa, would be tried for the deaths of anti-government protesters during the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Mubarak's resignation was followed by a series of arrests of, and travel bans on, high-profile figures on charges of causing the deaths of 300–500 demonstrators, injuring 5,000 more, embezzlement, profiteering, money laundering and human rights abuses.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Among those charged were Mubarak, his wife Suzanne, his sons Gamal and Alaa, former interior minister Habib el-Adly, former housing minister Ahmed El-Maghrabi, former tourism minister Zoheir Garana and former secretary for organizational affairs of the National Democratic Party Ahmed Ezz.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Mubarak's ouster was followed by allegations of corruption against other government officials and senior politicians.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 28 February 2011, Egypt's top prosecutor, Yehia Galal, ordered an assets freeze on Mubarak and his family.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This was followed by arrest warrants, travel bans and asset freezes for other public figures, including former parliament speaker Fathi Sorour and former Shura Council speaker Safwat El Sherif.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Arrest warrants were issued for financial misappropriations by public figures who left the country at the outbreak of the revolution, including former trade and industry minister Rachid Mohamed Rachid and businessman Hussein Salem; Salem was believed to have fled to Dubai.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Trials of the accused officials began on 5 March 2011, when former interior minister Habib el-Adli appeared at the Giza Criminal Court in Cairo.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In March 2011 Abbud al-Zumar, one of Egypt's best-known political prisoners, was freed after 30 years.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Founder and first emir of the Egyptian Islamic Jihad, he was implicated on 6 October 1981 assassination of Anwar Sadat.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 24 May, Mubarak was ordered to stand trial on charges of premeditated murder of peaceful protestors during the revolution; if convicted, he could face the death penalty.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The list of charges, released by the public prosecutor, was "intentional murder, attempted killing of some demonstrators ... misuse of influence and deliberately wasting public funds and unlawfully making private financial gains and profits".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The Egyptian and Tunisian revolutions sparked a wave of uprisings, with demonstrations spreading across the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Algeria, Bahrain, Iran, Jordan, Libya, Morocco, Yemen and Syria witnessed major protests, and minor demonstrations occurred in Iraq, Kuwait, Mauritania, Oman, Saudi Arabia, Somalia and Sudan.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The Egyptian protests were not centred around religion-based politics, but nationalism and social consciousness.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Before the uprising, the best-organised and most-prominent opposition movements in the Arab world usually came from Islamist organisations with members who were motivated and ready to sacrifice.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] However, secular forces emerged from the revolution espousing principles shared with religious groups: freedom, social justice and dignity.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Islamist organisations emerged with a greater freedom to operate.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Although the cooperative, inter-faith revolution was no guarantee that partisan politics would not re-emerge in its wake, its success represented a change from the intellectual stagnation (created by decades of repression) which pitted modernity and Islamism against one another.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Islamists and secularists were faced with new opportunities for dialogue on subjects such as the role of Islam and Sharia in society, freedom of speech and the impact of secularism on a predominantly Muslim population.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Despite the optimism surrounding the revolution, commentators expressed concern about the risk of increased power and influence for Islamist forces in the country and region and the difficulty of integrating different groups, ideologies and visions for the country.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Journalist Caroline Glick wrote that the Egyptian revolution foreshadowed a rise in religious radicalism and support for terrorism, citing a 2010 Pew Opinion poll which found that Egyptians supported Islamists over modernizers by an over two-to-one margin.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Another journalist, Shlomo Ben-Ami, said that Egypt's most formidable task was to refute the old paradigm of the Arab world which sees the only choices for regimes repressive, secular dictatorships or repressive theocracies.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Ben-Ami noted that with Islam a central part of the society, any emergent regime was bound to be attuned to religion.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In his view, a democracy which excluded all religion from public life (as in France) could succeed in Egypt but no genuine Arab democracy could disallow the participation of political Islam.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Since the revolution Islamist parties (such as the Muslim Brotherhood) have strengthened in the democratic landscape, leading constitutional change, voter mobilization and protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This was a concern of the secular and youth movements, who wanted elections to be held later so they could catch up to the already-well-organised groups.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Elections were held in September 2011, with Liberty and Justice (the Muslim Brotherhood party) winning 48.5 per cent of the vote.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In 2014 in Upper Egypt, several newspapers reported that Upper Egypt wanted to secede from the rest of the country to improve its standard of living.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Early on New Year's Day 2011 a bomb exploded in front of an Alexandria church, killing 23 Coptic Christians.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Egyptian officials said that "foreign elements" were behind the attack.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Other sources claim that the bomb killed 21 people only and injured more than 70.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Some Copts accused the Egyptian government of negligence; after the attack, many Christians protested in the streets (with Muslims joining later).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] After clashing with police, protesters in Alexandria and Cairo shouted slogans denouncing Mubarak's rule in support of unity between Christians and Muslims.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Their sense of being let down by national security forces was cited as one of the first grievances sparking 25 January uprising.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 7 February a complaint was filed against Habib al-Adly (interior minister until Mubarak dissolved the government during the protests' early days), accusing him of directing the attack.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Egyptian women have been participating actively in the revolution, in the same way that they played an active role in the strike movement in the few last years, in several cases pressurizing the men to join the strikes.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In earlier protests in Egypt, women only accounted for about 10 per cent of the protesters, but on Tahrir Square they accounted for about 40 to 50 per cent in the days leading up to the fall of Mubarak.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Women, with and without veils, participated in the defence of the square, set up barricades, led debates, shouted slogans and, together with the men, risked their lives.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Some participated in the protests, were present in news clips and on Facebook forums and were part of the revolution's leadership during the Egyptian revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In Tahrir Square, female protesters (some with children) supported the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The diversity of the protesters in Tahrir Square was visible in the women who participated; many wore head scarves and other signs of religious conservatism, while others felt free to kiss a friend or smoke a cigarette in public.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Women organised protests and reported events; female bloggers, such as Leil Zahra Mortada, risked abuse or imprisonment by keeping the world informed of events in Tahrir Square and elsewhere.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Among those who died was Sally Zahran, who was beaten to death during one of the demonstrations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] NASA reportedly planned to name one of its Mars exploration spacecraft in Zahran's honour.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The participation and contributions by Egyptian women to the protests were attributed to the fact that many (especially younger women) were better educated than previous generations and represent more than half of Egyptian university students.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This is an empowering factor for women, who have become more present and active publicly.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The advent of social media also provided a tool for women to become protest leaders.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The Egyptian Armed Forces initially enjoyed a better public reputation than the police did; the former was seen as a professional body protecting the country, and the latter was accused of systemic corruption and lawless violence.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] However, when the SCAF cracked down on protesters after becoming the *de facto* ruler of Egypt the military's popularity decreased.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] All four Egyptian presidents since the 1950s have a military background.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Key Egyptian military personnel include defence minister Tantawi and armed forces chief of staff Sami Hafez Enan.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The Egyptian military numbers about 468,500 active personnel, plus a reserve of 479,000.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] As head of Egypt's armed forces, Tantawi has been described as "aged and change-resistant" and is attached to the old regime.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] He has used his position as defence minister to oppose economic and political reform he saw as weakening central authority.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Other key figures (Sami Hafez Anan chief among them) are younger, with closer connections to the US and the Muslim Brotherhood.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] An important aspect of the relationship between the Egyptian and American military establishments is the $1.3 billion in annual military aid provided to Egypt, which pays for American-made military equipment and allows Egyptian officers to train in the US.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Guaranteed this aid package, the ruling SCAF is resistant to reform.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] One analyst, conceding the military's conservatism, says it has no option but to facilitate democratisation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] It will have to limit its political role to continue good relations with the West, and cannot restrict Islamist participation in a genuine democracy.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] American political scientist Nathan Toronto coined the term "coupvolution" to describe the military's consolidation of power after the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The military has led a violent crackdown on the Egyptian revolution since the fall of Mubarak.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 9 March 2011 military police violently dispersed a sit-in in Tahrir Square, arresting and torturing protesters.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Seven female protesters were forcibly subjected to virginity tests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] During the night of 8 April 2011 military police attacked a sit-in in Tahrir Square by protesters and sympathetic military officers, killing at least one.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 9 October the Egyptian military crushed protesters under armed personnel carriers and shot live ammunition at a demonstration in front of the Maspero television building, killing at least 24.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 19 November the military and police engaged in a continuous six-day battle with protestors in the streets of downtown Cairo and Alexandria, killing nearly 40 and injuring over 2,000.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 16 December 2011 military forces dispersed a sit-in at the Cabinet of Ministers building, killing 17.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Soldiers fired live ammunition and attacked from the rooftop with Molotov cocktails, rocks and other missiles.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Foreign governments in the West (including the US) regarded Mubarak as an important ally and supporter in the Israeli–Palestinian peace negotiations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] After wars with Israel in 1948, 1956, 1967 and 1973, Egypt signed a peace treaty in 1979 (provoking controversy in the Arab world).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] According to the 1978 Camp David Accords (which led to the peace treaty), Israel and Egypt receive billions of dollars in aid annually from the United States; Egypt received over US$1.3 billion in military aid each year, in addition to economic and development assistance.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] According to Juan Cole many Egyptian youth felt ignored by Mubarak, feeling that he put the interests of the West ahead of theirs.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The cooperation of the Egyptian regime in enforcing the blockade of the Gaza Strip was deeply unpopular with the Egyptian public.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The 6 April Youth Movement (Arabic: حركة شباب 6 أبريل) is an Egyptian Facebook group begun in spring 2008 to support workers in El-Mahalla El-Kubra, an industrial town, who were planning to strike on 6 April.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Activists called on participants to wear black and stay home the day of the strike.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Bloggers and citizen journalists used Facebook, Twitter, Flickr, blogs and other media tools to report on the strike, alert their networks about police activity, organize legal protection and draw attention to their efforts.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] *The New York Times* has called it the political Facebook group in Egypt with the most dynamic debates.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In March 2012 it had 325,000 predominantly young and members, most previously inactive politically, whose concerns included free speech, nepotism in government and the country's stagnant economy.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Their Facebook forum features intense and heated discussions, and is frequently updated.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] According to political scientist Shingo Hamanaka (2020), social media networks such as Facebook and Twitter did not act as isolated triggers of the 2011 Revolution but as mobilizing tools that connected pre-existing activist groups like 6 April Youth Movement to a broader audience.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Hamanaka's analysis of two data sets show that individuals who were already highly engaged online, were significantly more likely to join street demonstrations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The study distinguishes between two groups, "early movers," who organized protests through digital platforms, and "late followers," who were influenced on digital platforms when widespread mass demonstrations began.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] We are all Khaled Said is a Facebook group which formed in the aftermath of Said's beating and death.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The group attracted hundreds of thousands of members worldwide, playing a prominent role in spreading (and drawing attention to) the growing discontent.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] As the protests began, Google executive Wael Ghonim revealed that he was behind the account.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] He was later detained for a few days until the government was able to get a hold of certain information that they needed.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Many questions were left around that subject, no one really understood what had actually happened or what has had been said.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In a TV interview with SCAF members after the revolution, Abdul Rahman Mansour (an underground activist and media expert) was disclosed as sharing the account with Ghonim.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Another online contribution was made by Asmaa Mahfouz, an activist who posted a video challenging people to publicly protest.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Facebook had previously suspended the group because some administrators were using pseudonyms, a violation of the company's terms of service.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] As one Egyptian activist tweeted during the protests, "We use Facebook to schedule the protests, Twitter to coordinate, and YouTube to tell the world." Internet censorship has also been extensive, in some cases to the extent of taking entire nations virtually offline.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Facebook, Twitter and blogging helped spread the uprising.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Egyptian businessman Khaled Said was beaten to death by police in June 2010, reportedly in retaliation for a video he posted showing Egyptian police sharing the spoils of a drug bust.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Wael Ghonim's memorial Facebook page to Said grew to over 400,000 followers, creating an online arena where protestors and those discontented with the government could gather and organise.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The page called for protests on 25 January, later known as the "Day of Wrath".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Hundreds of thousands of protestors flooded the streets to show their discontent with murder and corruption in their country.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Ghonim was jailed on 28 January, and released 12 days later.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Egyptian activist and 6 April Youth Movement member Asmaa Mahfouz posted a video urging the Egyptian people to meet her at Tahrir Square, rise up against the government and demand democracy.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In the video, she spoke about four protesters who had immolated themselves in protest of 30 years of poverty and degradation.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On 24 January Mahfouz posted another video relating efforts made in support of the protest, from printing posters to creating flyers.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The videos were posted on Facebook and then YouTube.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The day after her last video post, hundreds of thousands of Egyptians poured into the streets in protest.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Since 25 January 2011, videos (including those of a badly beaten Khaled Said, disproving police claims that he had choked to death), tweets and Facebook comments have kept the world abreast of the situation in Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Amir Ali documents the ways in which social media was used by Egyptian activists, Egyptian celebrities and political figures abroad to fan the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Democracy Now! journalist Sharif Abdel Kouddous provided live coverage and tweets from Tahrir Square during the protests, and was credited with using social media to increase awareness of the protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The role of social media in the Egyptian uprising was debated in the first edition of the Dubai Debates: "Mark Zuckerberg – the new hero of the Arab people?" Amir Ali has argued that, based in part on the Egyptian revolution, social media may be an effective tool in developing nations.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Some protesters discouraged the use of social media.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] A widely circulated pamphlet by an anonymous activist group titled "How to Protest Intelligently" (Arabic: كيف للاحتجاج بذكاء؟), asked readers "not to use Twitter or Facebook or other websites because they are all being monitored by the Ministry of the Interior".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Television, particularly live coverage by *Al Jazeera English* and BBC News, was important to the revolution; the cameras provided exposure, preventing mass violence by the government in Tahrir Square (in contrast to the lack of live coverage and more-widespread violence in Libya).
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Its use was important in order to portray the violence of the Egyptian government, as well as, building support for the revolution through several different mediums.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] On one front was social media giving minute by minute updates via YouTube, Facebook and Twitter, and in the other hand was the use of the mainstream media to report to a wider audience about the overall developments occurring in Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The ability of protesters to focus their demonstrations on a single area (with live coverage) was fundamental in Egypt but impossible in Libya, Bahrain and Syria, irrespective of social-media use.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] A social-media expert launched a network of messages with the hashtag #jan25 on 11 February 2011, when Mubarak's resignation was announced.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Social media helped secure solidarity for the revolutionaries from people outside of Egypt.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This is evident through movements like the "March of Millions", "Voice of Egypt Abroad", "Egyptians Abroad in Support of Egypt" and "New United Arab States", who had their inception during the revolution inside the realms of Twitter and Facebook.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Journalism scholar Heather Ford studied the use of infoboxes and cleanup templates in the Wikipedia article regarding the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Ford claims that infoboxes and cleanup tags were used as objects of "bespoken-code" by Wikipedia editors.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] By using these elements, editors shaped the news narrative in the first 18 days of the revolution.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Ford used the discussion page and the history of edits to the page.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] She shows how political cartoons were removed, and how the number of casualties became a source of heated debate.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Her research exemplifies how editors coordinated and prioritised work on the article, but also how political events are represented through collaborative journalism.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] During the early morning hours of 28 January the Mubarak regime shut down internet and cell phone networks in the whole country.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This media shutdown was likely one of the reasons why the numbers of protestors exploded on 28 January.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] While the regime disrupted the media, people needed to engage in face-to-face communication on a local level, which the regime could not monitor or control.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] In such a situation it is more likely that radicals will influence their neighbours, who are not able to see the public opinion displayed in social media, therefore these people are then more likely to also engage in civil unrest.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] This vicious circle can be explained through a threshold model of collective behaviour, which states that people are more likely to engage in risky actions if other people inside their networks (neighbours, friends, etc.) have taken action.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Radicals have a small threshold and are more likely to form new networks during an information blackout, influencing the people.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Disrupting the media and communication had 2 main results: it increased the local mobilisation of people and empowered radicals who influenced their surroundings, which resulted in an increase in protests.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] During 28 January the increased local mobilisation pushed a large amount of apolitical Egyptians into action, either to look after their friends and family in the absence of mobile communication or to complain about the shutdown, resulting in large protests not only in Cairo.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Meanwhile, the Mubarak regime was unable to communicate a possible threat to the protestors via social media and was therefore unable to dissuade the crowds through this mean, which spread the protests further.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] The 25 January Revolution and the fall of Hosni Mubarak the following month ushered in a new artistic era reflecting a changed social and political environment; "the revolution triggered a new public culture".
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Since its beginning, artists played a significant role in the protests; street art and music (*electro* or *techno sha'bi*) were used to craft a public culture.
[src:c-span/2011-egyptian-revolution-p02] Artists documented and captured the essence of the revolution, distributing their art through online and face-to-face social networks.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 2012.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic president Barack Obama and his running mate, incumbent vice president Joe Biden, were elected to a second term.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They defeated the Republican ticket of former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney and Wisconsin congressman Paul Ryan.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama and Biden were re-nominated by their party without strong opposition in the way.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, the Republican Party experienced a competitive primary, with Romney consistently competitive in the polls and winning the support of many party leaders, but facing challenges from a number of more conservative contenders.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney secured his party's nomination in May, defeating former senator Rick Santorum, former speaker of the House and Georgia congressman Newt Gingrich, and Texas congressman Ron Paul, among other candidates.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaigns focused heavily on domestic issues, and debate centered largely around sound responses to the Great Recession along with long-term federal budget issues, the future of social insurance programs, and the Affordable Care Act.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Foreign policy was also discussed, including the end of the Iraq War in 2011, military spending, the Iranian nuclear program, and appropriate counteractions to terrorism.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney claimed Obama's domestic policies were ineffective and financially insolvent while Obama's campaign sought to characterize Romney as a plutocratic businessman who was out of touch with the average American.
[src:c-span/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaign was marked by a sharp rise in fundraising, including from nominally independent Super PACs.
